<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France "Very Worried" About New Israeli Blockade of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is "very
worried" about the effects of the new blockade by Israel of the
Palestinian territory of West Bank, saying that this measure would
make it impossible for Palestinians to go to holy places in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"This situation, which is not new, is particularly badly
experienced in this period of the festival of Aid al-Adha
(festival of sacrifice of Muslims). This is why France hopes that
the Palestinians, whatever their religious belief, could have free
access to the holy places, " said French Foreign Ministry
spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Citing risks of terrorist attacks, Israel imposed a new
blockade upon the West Bank Tuesday evening one day after it
lifted it.
</P>
<P>
On the Euro-Mediterranean conference held this week in Veletta,
Malta, the spokesman said that although this conference failed to
solve any problem, it "began to create the conditions more
favorable to the de-blockade of the peace process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Slips as Exports Reach Record Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit dropped
slightly to 11.6 billion U.S. dollars in February as increased
demand for civilian aircraft and chemicals helped stimulate U.S.
exports to a record high, the Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The February trade imbalance was 8.5 percent lower than
January's deficit of 12.7 billion dollars, which is the highest
figure on record since the government adopted a new system of
tracking the monthly flows of both goods and services.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports of goods and services in the month were up 4
percent to an all-time high of 73.5 billion dollars. Imports also
set a record high, climbing 2.1 percent to 85.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the export side, sales of American civilian aircraft rose by
625 million dollars to a total of 1.7 billion dollars. Other
sizable gains were recorded in sales of telecommunications
equipment, chemicals, machinery and computer chips.
</P>
<P>
On the import side, demand for foreign cars and parts was up
2.4 percent to 12.3 billion dollars which double the total of U.S.
automotive exports.
</P>
<P>
America's foreign oil imports were up 14 percent in February to
5.7 billion dollars on a seasonally adjusted basis. The volume of
crude oil imports shot up by 12.4 percent although the price fell
by 8.1 percent from an average of 21.99 dollars per barrel in
January.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit with Japan narrowed by 0.9 percent to
4.3 billion dollars, but for the first two months of the year the
deficit is running 11 percent higher over the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Canada dropped by 12.8 percent to 1.48 billion
dollars as U.S. exports to Canada rose sharply to 12.1 billion
dollars, the highest total in history for any single country. The
deficit with Mexico was down 1.1 percent to 1.27 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Even with the small improvement, the U.S. trade deficit for the
year was running at an annual rate of 145.6 billion dollars, a
sharp increase from an imbalance of 114.3 billion dollars for
1996, which was the worst in eight years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
