<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Kohl Begin Talks on NATO, War Trophies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
began a one-day meeting with visiting Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in the spa town of Baden-Baden in Germany's Black Forest.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to discuss NATO's eastward
expansion and the fate of War World II trophy art -- some one
million German art treasures, two million rare books and ancient
archives -- seized by then Soviet Union in 1945 from defeated
Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin supports the return of the art treasures to Germany,
but the Russian parliament has passed a law declaring the works
the property of the Russian state.
</P>
<P>
The trophies, reportedly worth 65 billion US dollars, include
paintings by Monet, Degas, Renoire, El Greco, Goya, Rembrandt and
Rubens and a legendary golden treasure unearthed by German
archaeologist Heinrich Schliemann in Troy.
</P>
<P>
Russian sources said Yeltsin will return a few art objects to
Kohl during his two-day stay in Baden-Baden as a sign of good
will.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was initially scheduled as a ceremony for Yeltsin
to receive a "Man of the Year" award by a German media group, but
was upgraded to summit-level talks, partly given the pressing
issue of NATO's eastward expansion which Russia opposes.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Moscow and NATO on a new security
partnership charter due to be signed in Paris on May 27 have
stalled.
</P>
<P>
Russia is demanding a binding charter that NATO will not deploy
troops or nuclear weapons on the territories of its would-be
member states -- former members of Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, accompanied by his wife and daughter, arrived in
Germany Wednesday afternoon and will go home tomorrow. This is his
second foreign trip since his heart operation last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
