<HEADLINE> Irish Government Mourns Former Israeli President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government has paid
tributes to former Israeli president Chaim Herzog, who died at the
age of 78 early today, saying he was "a distinguished Irishman."
</P>
<P>
Alan Shatter, chairman of Ireland's joint foreign affairs
committee, was quoted by reports from Dublin as saying today that
Herzog, who was born in 1918 in Belfast, was a "man of great
intellect and dynamism."
</P>
<P>
"He was sincerely committed to peace and reconciliation between
Israel, neighboring Arab states and Palestinians. His passing will
be deeply mourned by all those who had the privilege of knowing
him," Shatter said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is reported as preparing for a state
funeral for Herzog, who was Israel's president for a decade until
1993 when he was succeeded by Ezer Weizman. 
</P>
