<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Prices Expected to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- All is set for the commencement of
Zimbabwe's tobacco marketing season with over 214,000 tonnes of a
much improved tobacco crop expected to go under the hammer at an
average price higher than last year's.
</P>
<P>
The volume of the crop to go through the sales, which open on
April 22 and 28 in Harare and Mutare of east Zimbabwe
respectively, will, however, be lower than that of the previous
year because of incessant rains which caused water logging,
Tobacco Marketing Board Chairman Njodzi Machirori said here
today.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the indications are that the demand is going to exceed
supply this year given the situation in Europe among the cigarette
manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
He added there were chances the highest ever price of 1991 of 305
US cents per kilogram would be realised this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year's crop fetched an average 294 US cents per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is a major producer of tobacco in the world. enditem
