<HEADLINE> Mandela Officially Invites Mobutu to Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela had formally invited Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko to
hold peace talks with rebel leader Laurent Kabila in South Africa, a
senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad made the
announcement after Mandela held talks with Kabila and Mobutu's
special envoy Honore Ngbanda respectively last night.
</P>
<P>
Pahad, co-Chairman of the Zairean negotiations in South Africa,
told a press conference in Cape Town that Mandela and Kabila
discussed transitional arrangements for all levels of government in
Zaire to effect a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
Kabila reiterated his commitment to a peaceful negotiated
settlement to the conflict in Zaire, Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of this meeting and consultations with Mr. Mobutu's
adviser Mr. Ngbanda...President Mandela extended today a formal
invitation to Mr. Mobutu to meet Mr. Kabila in South Africa as early
as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident there will be a meeting (between Mobutu and
Kabila) soon," Pahad said, adding that "it could be any day now."
