<HEADLINE> Cameroun: Economic Operators Educated on Fiscal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The administration of North West
Province of Cameroun has warned that ignorance of fiscal obligations
would no longer be tolerated as an excuse for not paying taxes
regularly, the local paper "Cameroun Tribune" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made by Mbamba Firam, the Economic Adviser to
North West governor, during a meeting held in the provincial
capital Bamenda recently, aimed at educating and sensitizing
economic operators in Bamenda on their rights and obligations in the
payment of taxes.
</P>
<P>
Organised by the Provincial Center for Taxation in Bamenda, the
meeting also acquainted the economic operators with recent changes
in assessment systems.
</P>
<P>
The economic adviser decried the poor tax returns in the
province, saying they do not reflect the potentials of the
province. Mbamba Firam upheld that the empty treasuries are an
indication that people are not couscious of their fiscal
obligations.
</P>
<P>
He said according to available statistics, regular tax payers
in the province represent about 60 percent while the irregular
ones represent 40 percent. Among the irregular ones, some make
insufficient declarations and some make no declarations at all.
</P>
<P>
The administrator pointed out that if economic operators become
conscious of their obligations and declare their taxes regularly,
the quota of tax contribution by the population to the budget would
be attained and even doubled. enditem

