<HEADLINE> Cameroun Against Use of Fake, Expired Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The people in Bamenda, the
capital of North West Province of Cameroun, have been warned
against the use of fake and expired goods.
</P>
<P>
In a press release received in Yaounde today, Ndifor Akaagho,
the provincial delegate of industrial and commercial development,
stressed that the liberalisation of the nation's economy does not
mean that "sub-standard and poisonous goods" should be sold in
public.
</P>
<P>
Some unscrupulous business men and women have taken upon
themselves to sell expired goods including drugs in the markets.
The selling and buying of fake and expired items in Bamenda
markets is jeopardising commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
Such acts, the release states, are "criminal and must be
checked".
</P>
<P>
Against this background, a team will soon be on the field to
track down those involved in the business of selling fake and
expired goods.
</P>
<P>
A list of goods that are not expected in Bamenda markets was made
known to the public. Such goods will be confiscated and destroyed.
enditem

