<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) said here today that
the international community should preserve and improve the
environment for developing countries to participate in the world
economic and social globalization and regionalization process
effectively.
</P>
<P>
In a report entitled "the Economic and Social Survey of Asia
and the Pacific 1997," ESCAP noted that the majority of the least
developed countries and the economies in transition in the region
have not yet been able to participate meaningfully in the process
due to lack of the minimum development requirement.
</P>
<P>
The present conditions in these countries, characterized by low
per capital income, domestic savings and investment, make it
unlikely for them to meet the requirement on their own or to avail
themselves of the benefits of globalization and regionalization,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
They will continue to need strong support in terms of official
development assistance for the foreseeable future, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
"A major way in which the international community can assist
developing countries' integration into the global economy is to
ensure full implementation of the Uruguay Round in respect of
market access for developing countries' export products," it said.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, particular mention should be made of textiles
and clothing,' the report stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian and Pacific region accounts for more than 40 percent
of world exports of clothing, and for many individual countries in
the region, textiles and clothing represent as much as a quarter
of manufactured exports," it added.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that China, India, Indonesia, Malaysia,
South Korea and Thailand have been targeted for anti-dumping
actions by developed countries at one time or the other.
</P>
<P>
The use of anti-dumping measures as a protective device should
be strongly discouraged, particularly because many developing
countries may find it difficult to seek relief through costly
dispute settlement procedures, it said.
</P>
<P>
Some developed countries use their national laws to practise,
in effect, managed trade in order to secure a bilateral trade
balance, and such practices should be avoided, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Costs in Britain Fall in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The cost of doing business in
Britain fell steadily last year after sharp increases in 1994 and
1995 and is set to remain under tighter control, according to a
study published today.
</P>
<P>
The study by the Henley Center, an economic forecasting group,
said business costs, which include insurance, wages, property, raw
material, fuel, and banking and other charges, dropped by 1.2
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that lower raw material prices, falling bank
charges coupled with declining telecommunications costs largely
contributed to the fall.
</P>
<P>
But in the previous two years, business costs rose by about
five percent a year, well in excess of retail price inflation,
mainly due to higher raw material and fuel charges, which have
since been reversed by the strength of the pound.
</P>
<P>
The study forecast that technology, work patterns and
favorable trends in fuel, raw materials, banking and property
will keep the brake on costs for the rest of the decade.
</P>
<P>
It believed that the heat has gone out of the pay issue and
that a lower inflation rate will also have a powerful influence in
keeping business costs under control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
