<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Expects UN Representative in Direct Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot side expects a
diplomat of international standing will represent U.N. chief Kofi
Annan in the U.N.-proposed face-to-face talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides for a solution to the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing today, government
spokesman Manolis Christofides said that U.N. Secretary-General
Annan hopes and expects that direct negotiations on the
substance of the Cyprus issue could be able to begin by June or
July, if everything goes well by then.
</P>
<P>
The representative who will represent the U.N. Chief in the
face-to-face talks, if they begin, will have to be a diplomat of
international standing, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
"These meetings will take place day in, day out and the
Secretary-General is expected to preside over them for a certain
period, but due to his other commitments he cannot be
continuously present," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman welcomed the ongoing preparatory efforts, which
will lead to face-to-face negotiations between Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, and
praised the U.N. for making coordinating efforts.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides have entered the sixth week, during which
U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel had bi-weekly
separate meeting with Clerides and Denktash in a bid to prepare
the ground for face-to-face negotiations, and to get the two
sides to adopt good-will gestures.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said today that no common ground had been found so
far on substantive issues like security, territorial adjustments
and displaced persons, adding that "all these matters are still
pending."
</P>
<P>
As regards the proximity talks, Clerides said "it is too
early to say at this stage whether we are now closer to direct
negotiations. I do not think we can say that for at least another
two to three weeks."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that the National Council, the
President's top advisory body on the handling of the Cyprus
issue, which was made up of parliamentary party leaders, will
assess the situation and give the green light for the Greek
Cypriot side's participation in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a Greek
Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Jobless Figure Creates Doubts over Its Validity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of Britain's
unemployment continued to decline last month at 6.1 percent of the
workforce, but the official figure has aroused doubts over its
validity.
</P>
<P>
The headline unemployment level in March fell by 41,000 to 1.7
million, after adjusting for seasonal effects, its lowest level
for six and a half years, according to the Office for National
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said the figure, which
measures only those unemployed who also claim benefit, masked a
significantly higher real jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary challenged Brown to
say if a Labor government would change the basis of calculating
labor market statistics.
</P>
<P>
Professor Adrian Smith, president of the Royal Statistical
Society, said, no single figure of unemployment can "do justice to
the complexity of the labor market".
</P>
<P>
"Public concern over the validity of unemployment statistics
will not go away until the next government takes steps to improve
their basis," the professor added.
</P>
<P>
The Government figures are based on the record of those who
claim benefits for being out of work from Employment Service
Offices.
</P>
<P>
Since May 1979 these statistics have been altered as many as 32
times, most recently in October as a result of the replacement of
unemployment benefit by the more rigorously enforced job-seekers'
Allowance.
</P>
<P>
Even the Office for National Statistics acknowledged that the
headline rate continued to be distorted by last year's
introduction of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the office said it was impossible to calculate
an underlying employment trend, although the fall in jobless over
the last six months clearly exceeded the 15,000-20,000 a month
recorded in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
However, some of the economic observers here argued that the
figures issued by the Office for National Statistics are "too good
to be true".
</P>
<P>
Anne Green at the Institute for Employment Research at Warwick
University said: "The UK unemployment rate provides only a partial
picture of the extent of joblessness in the labor market."
</P>
<P>
The quarterly Labor Force Survey, which uses the International
Labor Organisation's definition of unemployment, estimates there
are an additional 2.549 million people in Britain who are not in
work.
</P>
<P>
Anne Green said "We need a much broader view than that provided
by the conventional definition of unemployment."
</P>
<P>
Employment researchers here suggest that Britain should have a
range of narrower and broader measures of unemployment and
underemployment as in the US where seven different categories are
used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
