<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Pubic Borrowing Falls to 22.8 bn Pounds in 1996-97 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain's public finances improved
over the past financial year as the government borrowed 3.6
billion pounds (5.8 billion US dollars) less than the Treasury had
forecast, according to the Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
ONS figures showed that the gap between government spending and
receipts was 8.8 billion pounds (14.3 billion US dollars) in
March, against economists' expectation of a nine billion pounds
(14.6 billion US dollars) shortfall and a 9.5 billion pounds (15.4
billion US dollars) figure for the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
This took total government borrowing in the 1996-97 financial
year which ended last month to 22.8 billion pounds (36.9 billion
US dollars), below the Treasury's forecast of 26.4 billion pounds
(42.8 billion US dollars) and the 31.7 billion pounds (51.4
billion US dollars) deficit recorded the previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
The better than expected figures reflected a surge in
corporation tax and other revenues and tight control of spending
by government departments, the ONS said.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke seized on the
figures to claim that the Conservatives would balance the budget
by the end of the decade if re-elected.
</P>
<P>
"Today's excellent figures are further evidence of he healthy
state of Britain's public finances. We have the winning formula,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
However, economists said that the extra revenue was the result
of over-cautious or erroneous forecasts in the government's
estimates, not stronger economic growth, and the deficit was still
too high for this stage of the economic cycle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
