<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Aims to Clear Language Barrier in Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government is planning
to take concrete measures to change Ireland's status as the least
linguistic state within the European Union (EU) amid fears that
international companies needing of multi-lingual staff may decide
to locate elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, whose economy is booming over the past few years, is
facing fierce competition for the first time from multilingual
Europeans arriving in their hundreds to work for the growing
number of multinational customer service setting up in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Launching a government initiative to increase the number of
Irish computer and language graduates, Irish Enterprise and
Employment Minister Richard Bruton was reported as saying
Wednesday: "We could be the victim of our own success in
attracting large numbers of blue-chip multinationals to Ireland."
</P>
<P>
Under the government plan, 1,000 language students will be
placed abroad for up to six months to improve their language skills
while an extra 1,000 language places will be created in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Around 3,300 people in Ireland are employed in the customer
service sector, which is dominated by multinational computer and
software manufacturers such as Gateway 2000, Microsoft and IBM,
and the number is expected to rise to 5,000 by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Industrial analysts said that unless Ireland can increase the
number of language graduates, new jobs will be snapped up by
foreign nationals who already represent an estimated 33 percent of
the multinational customer service workforce in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
