<HEADLINE> Palestinians Watch Closely Israel's Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat has been monitoring closely the
developments of the current political crisis in Israel, which
might change the course of peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat today received a half-hour update of the latest
developments in the so-called "Bar-On for Hebron" scandal, which
deeply implicated Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu who is
 facing police charges for fraud and breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in Israel's history that a prime
minister has ever been charged by the police, and the
opposition is intensifying its campaign to bring down the
hardline Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
If the government steps down under the political pressure,
this would have tremendous implications on the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, which has been deadlocked because of Israel's
hardline policies.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that if new elections are held in
Israel, the dovish Labor party would likely regain its power, and
bring the peace process back on track and proceed with it more
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian officials remained diplomatic and tight-lipped
about the scandal and its possible implications on the peace
process, terming it as "entirely Israel's internal matter."
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath told reporters that
he was uncertain about the possible impact of the Bar-On
affair over the peace process, but he admited that the PNA
was following the situation closely.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of entierly internal matter for the
Israelis. We do not see it fit for us to discuss it. But
I'm sure that it is a factor ... that must be seriously
considered in the coming few days," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
