<HEADLINE> Report: Ross Makes No Progress in Resuming Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East coordinator
Dennis Ross made no progress in resuming peace talks between the
Israelis and Palestinians after his meeting this afternoon with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Ross met Netanyahu and briefed him on his meeting with
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
Wednesday, but no progress has been reported, the report said,
adding that Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ross should return to Washington as there is no chance that
the peace talks with the Palestinians can resume at this time
because of the current political situation in Israel, the radio
quoted a government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Israel Television reported that the police team
investigating the Bar-On Affair has recommended that Netanyahu
be indicted, charging him with fraud and breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the history of the Jewish state that
the police have recommended the indictment of a prime minister.
However, Netanyahu said that he has no intention of resigning.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here Wednesday in an effort to restart peace
negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinians, met Netanyahu
Wednesday before traveling to Gaza for talks with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Ross is reportedly trying to hammer out a formula which will
get the two sides back to the negotiating table and end the
crisis which erupted with Israel's decision to start
construction of Jewish settlement on Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
After a half-hour meeting with Netanyahu Wednesday, Ross said
that a way has to be found to put the peace process back on track
and to ensure that violence is not going to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
"We also have to find a way to move the process forward in a
way which ensures that the hopes of each side can be realized and
that we have a credible negotiating process," said Ross.
</P>
<P>
Ross and Netanyahu did not discuss the proposal to advance the
final status talks between the Israelis and Palestinians, or the
second pullback of the Israeli army in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made it clear to Ross at their Wednesday meeting
that only the cessation of terrorism would lead to the
resumption of the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
