<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Stresses Importance of Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today underscored the importance of peacekeeping operations in
troubled parts of the world, saying the realisation of peace was
essential for governments to effectively deal with social problems
facing the people.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the end of a three-week southern African regional
peacekeeping demonstration exercise, code-named exercise blue hungwe,
in Nyanga of east Zimbabwe, Mugabe said the role played by military
forces in conflict resolution was necessary for the attainment of
peace.
</P>
<P>
With the attainment of peace, he said, governments of the world
would be able to divert their resources from conflict resolution to
the provision of basic necessities of humanity such as health,
housing, food and education.
</P>
<P>
He spoke in support of the concept of joint military training
exercises for defence forces of southern African countries, saying
this was one way peace could be promoted and preserved in the region.
</P>
<P>
''Demonstration such as blue hungwe removes suspicion and
increases transparency. It builds confidence, mutual trust and
understanding among participating defence forces at both political
and professional levels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said cooperation and co-existence among the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) nations had become extremely important
because the problems being faced had become so transnational that no
one nation could claim to have the ability and resources to deal with
them in isolation.
</P>
<P>
He suggested joint training operations for peacekeeping purposes
should be an annual event hosted on a rotational basis among southern
African countries in order to enhance the cooperation among the
defence forces of the region.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, the first large-scale multinational peacekeeping
operation in Africa, brought together 1,100 military personnel
from Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania and Zimbabwe.
