<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Remain in Power Despite Scandal (by Zhi Linfei) (I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today vowed to remain in power despite his
alleged involvement in a political scandal and the opposition's
call for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a party rally at the Likud headquarters in Tel
Aviv, Netanyahu said he loved a good fight and was confident
that he would continue leading the country till the year 2000
and even beyond.
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that he had received hundreds of calls
from his supporters to encourage him to go on leading the country
despite the political storm over his alleged role in a political
corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the state television Channel I revealed that
police investigators probing the so-called "Bar-On for Hebron"
scandal had recommended the state prosecution to charge
Netanyahu with breach of trust and fraud in appointing former
Jerusalem attorney Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general in
January.
</P>
<P>
Police investigators reportedly also recommended indicting
Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime Minister's Office
Director-General Avigdor Liberman and Shas party leader Aryeh
Deri, who allegedly pushed for the appointment of Bar-On in
order to gain from a plea bargain deal in his future bribery
trial.
</P>
<P>
Deri was said to have conditioned Shas support of the Hebron
agreement on Bar-On's appointment.
</P>
<P>
After three-month investigations, the police presented Tuesday
a 995-page report and recommendations to State Attorney Edada
Arbel and current Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein, who will
decide within the next few days whether to endorse the
recommendations or not.
</P>
<P>
The revelation about police indictment against Netanyahu has
caused a ripple throughout the political establishment and
shocked the public, because this is the first time in Israel's
history that a prime minister has ever been charged by the
police for corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
