<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Remain in Power Despite Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Netanyahu has been defending himself as innocent and blasting
the police recommendations against him for being
politically-motivated and intended to bring down his elected
government.
</P>
<P>
However, leading opposition parties Labor and Meretz
immediately demanded Netanyahu and his cabinet resign in order
to pave the way for new elections. Today, the Labor leadership
convened an urgent meeting in Tel Aviv to review the current
political crisis and the possibility of new elections.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Shimon Peres said he believed the current
crisis would surely lead to new elections for there was no other
way out.
</P>
<P>
Leading contender for Labor leadership Ehud Barak called on
all citizens, lawmakers and media leaders to work to overcome
the "tough moment" facing the nation by toppling the Likud
government.
</P>
<P>
In signs indicating the deep trouble that Netanyahu was
in, one of his major ruling partner the Third Way party convened
an urgent meeting today to discuss the implications of the
police investigation.
</P>
<P>
Party leader and Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani
has declared earlier that he would leave the coalition if any
minister was connected to the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, another major ruling partner Israel Ba'aliya party
will also hold a meeting on the current situation. Party leader
and Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky has also said
his party would withdraw support to the current government if
anyone within it was indicted.
</P>
<P>
Likud officials did not conceal their fears about the two
partners' rebel against the Likud-led coalition to bring it
down.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that even if the state prosecution
decided against indicting Netanyahu, serious damage has already
been inflicted on the current government and it is certain that
it can no longer function as usual. 
</P>
