<HEADLINE> UK's Major Allows MPs to Vote Freely on Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Major today
announced that he would allow members of parliament a "free vote"
on whether to join a European single currency in a bid to end
quarrels in his Conservative Party two weeks before the May 1
election.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in north-west England, Major said the free
vote was "almost certainly the right way to handle it."
</P>
<P>
His decision on the single currency issue, which has dogged his
efforts to unite his party for the past few years, was welcomed by
those Conservative MPs who are opposed to European integration.
</P>
<P>
Major admitted that he had little choice but to accept a free
vote as it would be hard to force MPs to vote for a single
currency if they opposed the project.
</P>
<P>
The shift over Europe came as Major fought to heal festering
divisions in his ruling party over Europe: the same issue that led
to his predecessor Margaret Thatcher being ousted as party leader
and prime minister seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Major said it was "frustrating" that some members of his party
were "unwisely" stepping out of line, referring that two junior
ministers and some other candidates decided to campaign against a
single currency in defiance of government policy, which is to wait
and see if it is in Britain's interest to join.
</P>
<P>
But Major's move was criticized by the opposition Labor Party.
Labor's economics spokesman Gordon Brown said: "We now have a
leader who has lost control of his party."
</P>
<P>
"It is an astonishing admission by the Chancellor that on a
vital economic decision he was not even consulted," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
