<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Assures Signing of NATO Charter in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (xinhua) -- Russian president Boris Yeltsin
assured the signing of NATO-Russia charter as expected in May
after talks with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today in the Black
Forest spa town of Baden-Baden.
</P>
<P>
"On May 27 the treaty will be signed in Paris -- this means we
must hurry," Yeltsin told a news conference after the one-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said he was "confident" that the charter would be
completed by the May 27 deadline. "Some 90 percent of the charter
is completed," he added, and the remaining part comprised the most
difficult aspect of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The charter, defining a new security partnership between NATO
and Russia, aims to clear the way for eastwards expansion of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). Negotiations on the
charter stalled earlier due to serious differences.
</P>
<P>
However, the differences remains after the one-day meeting
between Yeltsin and Kohl. Yeltsin repeated Moscow's demand for a
binding pledge that NATO would not deploy troops or nuclear
weapons on the territory of new member states -- expected to
include the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland.
</P>
<P>
NATO has made clear that it is not willing to give eternal
guarantees regarding conventional forces, though it sees no need
to station nuclear weapons any closer to Russia.
</P>
<P>
According to it, concession on the issue would result in a
military alliance with two classes of members. NATO was built from
the very beginning on the doctrine that an attack on any one of its
16 members would be considered an attack on all.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the NATO issue, Yeltsin and Kohl also discussed the
German demand for return of art and cultural treasures seized by
former Soviet Union in 1945 in the defeated Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told reporters he had returned to Kohl 11 packages of
documents and letters from Walther Rathenau, who was assassinated
in June 1922 four months after becoming the foreign minister of
the Weimar Republic.
</P>
<P>
"One must take the first step to untie this knot and I have now
done this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has showed his support for Germany's demand, but was
blocked by the Russian parliament which has repeatedly passed laws
that would declare the cultural treasures Russia's state property.
</P>
<P>
The about one million works of art, two million books and
ancient archives now are in the hands of Moscow, are reportedly
worth 65 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the objects are paintings by Monet, Degas, Renoire, El
Greco, Goya, Rembrandt and Rubens, as well as the legendary golden
treasure from Troy, unearthed by German archeologist Heinrich
Schliemann.
</P>
<P>
Russian culture minister Michail Schwydkoj earlier proposed
negotiations on the issue and said that it was a possible solution
to make the cultural treasures international.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also gave Kohl today a microfilm of the complete
documents from the former East German Communist Party's central
committee, as well as a list of things Moscow wanted back from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said German President Roman Herzog would return to
Russia the first objects during his scheduled visit to Moscow in
September, but did not release further details of the list.
</P>
<P>
In the company of his wife Naina and daughter-adviser Tatjana,
Yeltsin arrived in Germany on Wednesday afternoon and will leave
Baden-Baden early Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president would also receive a "Man of the Year"
award from a German media group later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
