<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Estonia today signed
two agreements regarding reciprocal investments and marine
transport during the talks between visiting Estonian Foreign
Minister Toomas Ilves and his Greek counterpart Theodoros
Pangalosn.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the talks, Ilves, currently on an
official visit to Greece, described his talks here as
"particularly important," saying that the two countries shared the
"very close" views on the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Ilves, the first Estonian foreign minister to visit Greece,
stressed that his country's foreign policy centered efforts on
accession to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pangalos said that the Estonia satisfied all the
prerequisites for the EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister also repeated Athens' position that all
Council of Europe member-states should be able to apply for
accession and with respect to those for which the European
Commission's opinion was positive, accession negotiations should
begin at the same time. 
