of Britain since it started in 1994, acting British High
Commissioner Alan Jones said here today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a ceremony at the Technical College to
mark the end of the Scientific, Instrumentation Repair and
Maintenance Course.
</P>
<P>
The course was particularly beneficial for a wide range of
Tanzania's institutions and bodies which had their representation
at the course, said Jones.
</P>
<P>
"This particular course is one of the 21 funded by ODA in
Tanzania training program since 1994, In 1996/97, the program
received over 570,000 of funding with the British Council being
deeply involved in the organization of the training," he said.
</P>
<P>
He handed at the ceremony over the equipment used in the
course to the Principal Secretary of the Ministry of Science,
Technology and Higher Education Abdallah Nogroro.
</P>
<P>
He said that the equipment will help the college in running
its practical programs effectively and in mounting short courses
for industry, both of which would have been impossible without
the equipment.
</P>
<P>
"Technical institutions strive for promotion of knowledge and
skills, especially the practical applications of scientific and
technical knowledge and skills at work places," he said
</P>
<P>
"As a result of rapid changes in the field of science and
technology, continuous interaction between technical institutions
and industry is very essential," he said. 
</P>
