<HEADLINE> S. African, Botswanan Firms Sign Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's leading
electricity supplier Eskom has signed a new agreement with its
Botswana counterpart BCP to enhance the cooperation between the
two companies, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued here, the agreement, replacing the
one signed in 1992, covers the supply of 400 MW of electricity on
a "firm basis", up from the 150 MW of the old one.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony on Wednesday in Gaborone,
capital of Botswana, Eskom's executive director for transmission
Piet Faling said the agreement was the first of the kind based on
the Southern African Power Pool trade schedules.
</P>
<P>
"It signals a new phase in our cooperation with each other,
and an important milestone in the economic development of our
region," said Faling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Botswana's electricity supplier BCP said the
agreement would be beneficial for both companies.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, characterized with the spirit of mutual respect
and encouragement, was a new highlight in its long relationship
with Eskom, said BCP. 
</P>
