<HEADLINE> Former US Defense Chiefs Support Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Three former U.S. defense
secretaries today issued a joint statement, urging the Senate to
ratify the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC).
</P>
<P>
Former defense secretaries William Perry, Harold Brown and
Eliott Richardson joined the current defense secretary, William
Cohen, in backing the treaty, which bans the development,
production, stockpiling, transfer and use of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff John
Shalikashvili reiterated his appeal to the Senate for ratifying
the convention.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that U.S. ratification of the CWC will
contribute significantly to the security interests of the United
States and safety of our armed forces," said the three former
defense secretaries in the brief statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement released by the Pentagon said, "In light of the
decision under President Reagan to get rid of the vast majority of
U.S. chemical weapons stockpiles, it is in our interests to
require other nations to do the same."
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed by 161 countries and ratified by 70 up to
now, will go into effect as of April 29 with or without the U.S.
ratification.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the treaty led by Chairman Jesse Helms of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee insisted that the treaty needs
to be amended before ratification.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, four other former defense secretaries, --
Dick Cheney, Caspar Weinberger, Donald Rumsfeld and James
Schlesinger -- urged the Senate not to ratify the treaty, arguing
that the treaty is not in the interests of the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
