<HEADLINE> Compaq Reports Big Gains, Apple Big Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Compaq Computer Corporation,
the world's largest personal computer manufacturer, reported
Wednesday earnings of 387 million U.S. dollars in the first
quarter of this year, up 65 percent from 234 million dollars in
the comparable period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Apple Computer Inc.. reported a big loss. For its
most recent quarter, which ended on March 28, Apple reported a net
loss of 708 million dollars, compared with a deficit of 740
million dollars, according to a report of the New York Times
today.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, sales of Compaq rose 14
percent to 4.81 billion dollars from 4.21 billion dollars in the
first quarter of 1996, and for the second quarter, Apple's sales
fell 27 percent to 1.60 billion dollars in the same quarter of
last year, which was historically Apple's weakest.
</P>
<P>
With a growth rate nearly twice that of the personal computer
industry as a whole, the newspaper noted, Compaq is taking market
share from weaker competitors. The personal computer giant is also
reaping the rewards of its move to become a computer systems
producer, like L.B.M. or Hewlett-Packard, supplying severs and
networking technology in addition to personal computer.
</P>
<P>
And Apple is seeking a friendly buyer. Oracle Corporation is
considering a bid of more than 1 billion dollars to acquire
Apple. Now Apple has introduced new Power Mac models which is
considered a bright prospect for the company. The new model is
equipped with processor speeds up to 300 megahertz and new
Powerbook portables with chips as fast as 240 megahertz, faster
than anything offered by companies using the Intel Corporation's
microprocessors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
