have appealed to the government to act swiftly by deploying army
units to quell the heavily-armed bandits in the bushes in
Karagwe, Biharawulo and Ngara districts.
</P>
<P>
Kagera regional police commader Juma Ng'wanang'waka told
reporters in the town of Bukoba today that three people including
a policeman were shot dead last Sunday morning when armed bandits
attacked two buses plying between Mwanza and Ngara.
</P>
<P>
He said about 30 bandits, armed with a light machine gun,
sub-machine guns and hand grenades, took away with some
properties and four guns seized from police officials.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, he noted that many Rwandan refugees, who
have been repatriated to Rwanda since January, are back in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He said between January to early this month, the police have
arrested a total of 645 Rwandan people, 300 of them at Lukole
refugee camp and 345 in the bush.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern over the refugees who were secretly
sneaking into the country, saying they poised security risk.
</P>
<P>
Some of the returning refugees carry fire arms with them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago, a Roman Catholic priest was ambushed at Uzuri
Wa Kondoo area in Karagwe District and was robbed almost all of
his properties. 
</P>
