<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Ex-Im Bank Pushes Commercial Aircraft Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import Bank
authorized 1.65 billion U.S. dollars in asset-based financing for
10 separate leases or sales of commercial aircraft in the first
half of fiscal year 1997, the bank announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The commercial airplanes were leased and sold by Boeing and
McDonnell Douglas to the emerging markets of the Czech Republic,
Egypt, India, Kenya, South Korea, Morocco, Turkey and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The bank also authorized a 105 million dollar long-term
guarantee for McDonnell Douglas MD-90 aircraft leases to China.
</P>
<P>
For the entire fiscal year 1996, the Ex-Im Bank's total
aircraft financing was some 1.25 billion dollars, and about 395
million dollars of this support was asset-based financing.
</P>
<P>
Asset-based financing, in which the aircraft serves as
collateral usually for a full-payout finance lease, is becoming
the most prevalent way of aircraft financing provided by the Ex-Im
Bank and other export credit agencies. Until the 1990s, most of
the bank's aircraft financing was in the form of a guarantee
backed by a sovereign guarantee from the buyer's government.
</P>
<P>
The bank is a government agency which finances and enhances the
exports of U.S. goods and services abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
