<HEADLINE> Business in Nepali Capital Halts Due to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The market of this capital city
of Nepal remained virtually closed for the whole day today as
local business community staged a strike against a new tax regime
to be imposed later this year.
</P>
<P>
Almost all main shops, companies and industrial units
throughout Kathmandu, except a few medicine stores, small retail
shops and restaurants, were closed all the day, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Even the often ubiquitous vegetable and fruit vendors were rare
seen in the streets in the day.
</P>
<P>
Industrialists and businessmen also took out a silent
procession around Downtown Kathmandu in protest of the
government's decision to introduce the Value Added Tax (VAT) from
November, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the protesters met with Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand after the procession and informed him that the new
VAT tax would be a burden for the country's business community and
consumers, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's business circles have been voicing strong protests
against the VAT system since the government decided to introduce
it two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen said the tax authorities and business community of
the country lack adequate preparations for the new tax.
</P>
<P>
They also warned that the implementation of VAT would aggravate
corruption, increase market prices and affect adversely on the
country's overall economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
