<HEADLINE> Vietnam, China Resume Second Passenger Train Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The passenger train service between
Vietnam's capital Hanoi and the southwestern Chinese city of
Kunming restarted today after a 17-year break.
</P>
<P>
The 32-hour through train service means passengers will no longer
have to change trains at the border between Vietnam and China.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the service was marked by an official
ceremony at Hanoi Railway Station and the departure of the first
train for Kunming. The journey costs about 30 U.S. dollars for
Vietnamese and Chinese and about 40 dollars for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Trains will operate every Friday and Sunday from both Hanoi and
Kunming and will stop at Lao Cai, a border town in Vietnam and
Hekou, Kai Yuan and Yi Liang in China.
</P>
<P>
The first direct passenger rail link between Hanoi and Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, China was re-opened at the beginning of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The track was built by the French about 100 years ago to carry
goods from south western China to the sea at Vietnam's port city
of Hai Phong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
