<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, ACP Discuss Future of Lome Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT (the Netherlands), April 18 (Xinhua) -- The European
Union members and the ACP (African, Caribbean and Pacific) states
started a meeting here today to discuss the future of the Lome
Convention, which governs economic and trade ties between the two
blocs.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the EU and ACP, most of which are former
colonies of European countries, are scheduled to discuss
financial, technological, trade and economic cooperation at the
two-day meeting, which will constitute the first step towards a
new Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
The current fourth Lome Convention, to which 70 ACP countries
are signatory, was signed in 1989 and expires in 2000. The two
sides have signed four conventions named after the Togan capital
Lome, where the first accord was signed in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Participants today discussed the general framework of the
convention and financial and technological cooperation and
tomorrow will focus on trade and economic cooperation and its
institutional and political dimensions.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by the Netherlands, which holds the
rotating EU presidency for the first half of 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
