<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Painting Sells 800,000 US dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- An ink and brush painting by late
Pan Tianshou, a renowned contemporary traditional Chinese painter,
sold for 6.6 million yuan (800,000 US dollars), the highest price
at today's China Guardian '97 Spring Auction.
</P>
<P>
The painting, titled "Warm Water in Spring Pond" and featuring
an ox, rocks, streams, and wild flowers, is regarded as one of
Pan's best artworks.
</P>
<P>
At the bottom price of 2.6 million yuan and after over 30
rounds of competition, the painting was eventually bought at 6.6
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The China Guardian Auction Co., Ltd, put 282 modern Chinese
paintings and calligraphy on the auction block, selling 232 for
19.25 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Today's buyers of artworks have indicated that they are
increasingly eyeing modern paintings, even while some have cast
their eyes on the ancient paintings." said Gan Xueping, vice
president of The China Guardian Auction Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
But a picture of well-known contemporary painter Zhang Daqian,
which had been predicted to be well sold before the auction, was
not sold.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yanyan, who is in charge of the Chinese paintings and
calligraphy category from Guardian, explained that it was due to
domestic collectors' inadequate understanding of Zhang's artworks
in his late years, and that it was not appropriate to auction such
paintings now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
