<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Egypt Are All-weather Friends, Says Jiang (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese president and Egyptian
prime minister agreed that China and Egypt are all-weather friends
during their talks held here today.
</P>
<P>
There are no conflicts in interest between China and Egypt,
only friendship and common wishes to strengthen bilateral
cooperation, said Chinese President Jiang Zemin when meeting with
visiting Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal Ahmed El-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
China is satisfied with the sustained, steady development of
Sino-Egyptian friendly cooperative ties which started some 40
years ago, said Jiang, calling the two countries "all-weather"
friends as their relations have stood the test of sweeping changes
in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
He said that as birthplaces of world civilization, both
China and Egypt have made significant contributions to the human
civilization and progress. The friendship between the two peoples
has experienced a long history.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the current international situation is still
facing complicated and profound changes, he said, the tendency
toward multi-polarity grows rapidly as does the quest for peace,
stability, and development.
</P>
<P>
The economic factor is playing an increasing role in
international relations. The world is expected to face a new era
of development.
</P>
<P>
However, the unjust and irrational international political and
economic order has not been changed fundamentally. The gap between
rich nations and poor nations continues to widen. Developing
countries are confronted with challenges as well as
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, developing countries should be more
unified and make concerted efforts to establish a more just and
rational international political and economic order, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President expressed China's willingness to
strengthen coordination and close cooperation with Egypt. China
wishes to make joint efforts with Egypt to establish long-term
friendly cooperative relations for the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
