<HEADLINE> "Dalai is welcome home if he stops splitting motherland": Chinese official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, April 18 (Xinhua) -- "We're willing to accept Dalai and
hope that he will return to the motherland so long as he stops
activities of splitting the motherland and seeking independence,"
said Sun Qiwen, vice chairman of the government of Tibetan
Autonomous Region in his meeting with Jan Egeland, state secretary
in the Foreign Ministry of Norway on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Sun expressed his appreciation of Norwegian
government's stand that Tibet is an inalienable part of the
Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about human rights, Sun noted that China, with the
support of the majority of voters, recently defeated at an
international human rights conference an anti-China draft
resolution, which included so-called "Tibet problem."
</P>
<P>
"This has proved that the conditions of human rights in China
has been affirmed and respected by the majority of countries and
people in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, Tibet enjoys social stability, fast economic
growth, and improving living standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
"People of all ethnic groups in Tibet are living and working in
peace and contentment and they are the masters of their own
affairs in every sense," Sun noted.
</P>
<P>
Since he arrived in Lhasa on April 15, Jan Egeland and his
group had toured Buddhist temples and a prison in Lhasa and held
discussions with the Tibetan Academy of Social Sciences, Tibetan
University, the Department of Transportation, and the Red Cross
Society.
</P>
<P>
Egeland said that he was impressed by the Chinese government's
painstaking efforts in protecting the ancient Tibetan culture and
temples.
</P>
<P>
He said Norway and Tibetan region should further develop
friendly cooperation in medicine and health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
