<HEADLINE> Indonesian FM to Visit Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas will go to Oman and Kuwait next week on a tour of "oil
diplomacy", a Foreign Ministry official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "oil diplomacy" is based on the prediction that
oil resources in Indonesia would dry up within 10 to 20 years,
Ibrahim Yusuf, director of the African and Middle East Affairs
Department of the Foreign Ministry, said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia could not maintain its annual economic growth of
around 8 percent without adequate oil resources, said Yusuf, who
will accompany the foreign minister on his Middle East tour.
</P>
<P>
He said the Persia Gulf is still the biggest source of oil and
gas in the world. The eight Gulf countries including Oman and
Kuwait produce 18.56 million barrel of oil per day or 25 percent
of the world's total oil production.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Oman and Kuwait from April 21 to 25, Alatas
is expected to have talks with government officials of the two
countries on matters of mutual concern, especially bilateral
relations, Yusuf said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas will also sign several agreements on energy cooperation
and other matters with the two countries, said Yusuf.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, in March this year, Alatas visited Qatar and the
United Arab Emirates for strengthening bilateral ties and trade,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
