<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung on Proposed Amendments to Two Ordinances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa today
made clear his major considerations concerning the proposed
amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order
Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tung's office published the Civil Liberties and
Social Order Consultation Document, to solicit public opinions
over the proposed amendments to the two ordinances.
</P>
<P>
The first consideration is that the amendments will be in
compliance with the Basic Law and the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), he told a press conference
held at his office.
</P>
<P>
Another consideration is that the many freedoms existing in the
territory will be maintained after the handover, including
freedoms of procession, assembly and speech, as these are part of
Hong Kong's culture and are among the few factors contributing to
Hong Kong's success.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he expected the local community to reach
consensus that Hong Kong's political organizations and directions
should be clear of foreign influences as this is critical to the
territory's stability.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's interference in local political development is also
prohibited, he emphasized, although he expected to see enhanced
links in the economic, cultural and personnel exchanges between
the Chinese mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan after July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Many countries in the world are very sensitive about foreign
political influences affecting their political thinking, and if
you look very carefully at the law of the United States on this
sort of matters, you will find the law there is much more
restrictive than what we are proposing here today," Tung
explained.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Public Order Ordinance, he expected a balance to
be struck between the rights of the individual and social order.
</P>
<P>
He noted that many famous cities in North America and Asia
would not give up control over public order, and they have
stricter provisions in their laws than those being proposed to the
Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Tung reassured that the amendments to the two ordinances are
"not directed against any particular persons or organizations."
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that the consultation process, scheduled to
last three weeks till April 30, is a genuine one.
</P>
<P>
Since the release of the document, he has met people from many
organizations and groups of the territory to listen to their
opinions about the proposed amendments, Tung said, while appealing
to the general public for their views. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
