<HEADLINE> China, Malaysia Signs Securities Regulatory Memorandum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), the industry watchdog, today signed a
memorandum of understanding on securities regulation and
cooperation with its Malaysian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the memorandum paved the way for closer
cooperation between the Chinese and Malaysian securities
regulators," said Zhou Daojiong, chairman of the CSRC.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the two sides will join hands in fields
such as regulatory information exchanges and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Zhou also mentioned that the CSRC is looking forward to closer
cooperation with the international securities regulators, so as to
draw their advanced experience in the area and enhance its own
regulation of securities market.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Securities Commission of Malaysia,
M. M. Abdul Majid, hailed the signing of the memorandum as "a
recognition of the need for the two regulatory organizations in
the development and regulation of our capital markets."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that a closer cooperation between the two sides
is "in anticipation of the needs of the securities investors in
China and Malaysia, and will safeguard mutual investment in the
securities markets in the two countries."
</P>
<P>
After six years of development, China's securities market has
taken shape. A total of 571 companies have been listed at the two
stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen by the end of March, with
a capitalization of 1.407 trillion yuan. And more than 2,500 stock
trading accounts are registered at the two stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
International capital market also provides Chinese enterprises
the needed funds. A total of 87 enterprises have issued foreign
investors-targeted B shares by the end of February, raising three
billion US dollars in foreign capital. The number of
overseas-listed firms also reached 29, pooling 5.9 billion US
dollars in the aggregate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
