<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Move for Preserving Peace in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhu Shixiang)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A three-week southern African
regional peacekeeping demonstration exercise, which ended on
Thursday in Zimbabwe, was described as a new move for promoting
and preserving peace in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named Blue Hungwe, the first joint
peacekeeping training exercise in Africa, was designed to equip
the forces from the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
with UN peacekeeping doctrines, command procedures and
strategies.
</P>
<P>
The operation came against the background of the need for an
African peacekeeping force following the hurdled mission in
Somalia which saw multi-national forces withdrawing from the Horn
of Africa country without fulfilling the UN mandate.
</P>
<P>
The exercise brought together about 1,700 troops, military
observers and civilian police from eight SADC countries and a
number of international non-governmental organizations, the
International Committee of the Red Cross and other humanitarian
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Jointly sponsored by the Zimbabwe national army (ZNA) and the
British government at a cost of over 900,000 US Dollars, the
exercise was in three phases coded Blue Jesa, Tsuro and Ijuba.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists at a border camp in Nyanga, Zimbabwe,
Director of the exercise ZNA Major-General Mike Nyambuya, who
served as UN deputy forces commander during the Somalia mission,
said that "the fact that we have been able to come together and
train as a region is a major achievement on its own. We have
created and enhanced the inter-operability of forces from SADC."
</P>
<P>
The SADC forces had during the exercise, said Nyambuya,
managed to establish a peacekeeping modus operating among
themselves and the UN relief agencies on the basis of "solid
working relations" which could be used in the future.
</P>
<P>
British military advisory training team commander, Brigadier
Adrian Naughten, also said the joint military training and
peacekeeping exercise had proved that the region's forces could
work and live together without problems, adding that "we were
simulating real war situation as much as possible, but within the
bounds of safety. There were no casualties or injuries."
</P>
<P>
Although there were no plans yet to establish a permanent
peacekeeping force in the region, the exercise would make it much
easier for the mobilization of regional forces in the event that
their services were needed.
</P>
<P>
The exercise has also helped in standardizing operation
procedures of forces in the region. It also helped bring
stability in the region through interaction of forces from
different countries.
</P>
<P>
The operation was expected to enhance African peacekeeping
capability, sub-regional cooperation and military skills by way
of a multi-national joint field training exercise in the tactics
and techniques of peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
Local observers held, by the time the series of exercises are
over, there should be a solid cadre of officers and men from most
of the SADC armies able to work together and trained to cope with
peacekeeping duties.
</P>
<P>
But the matter should not stop at a series of exercises, said
the observers, adding that the SADC military leadership should be
tasked by their civilian leaderships to work out plans to have
units assigned in permanent near readiness for deployment
anywhere in the region.
</P>
<P>
Such a force does not need to be kept assembled in one
place. That would be an unnecessary expense. But each country
could be invited to have the required types of unit available for
deployment on a few days notice and a small permanent military
co-ordination committee could keep in regular contact and have
prepared the necessary contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
The same philosophy applied to the military sector would cost
little but ensure the region could cope with emergencies, they
said.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that one major problem that most countries of
southern Africa could face if a regional peacekeeping force was
deployed would be the logistics.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the exercise should be the start of a new
role for SADC members, and the military and political leadership
should build on the successes of the exercise and ensure that if
ever the worse came to the worst, southern Africa would be ready
to cope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Set to Abolish Tariffs in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) will become a free trade area by
the year 2000, according to an East African Standard report today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium on doing business in the COMESA region
held here, COMESA Director of Trade and Customs Zewede Demise
said that some member countries had already reduced tariffs by 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the complete removal of tariff and non-tariff
barriers would facilitate trade and sustainable economic
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
He told the symposium attended by businessmen from Kenya and
Zambia that COMESA countries had introduced changes to streamline
documentation for import and export trade in the regional market.
</P>
<P>
Demise disclosed that COMESA had undertaken a trade
development program which identifies problems facing enterprises
in the region and gives taitor-made solutions free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA official urged the business community of the member
countries to utilize COMESA trade information network
which offers free information on the regional market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
