<HEADLINE> Poll Makes Final at World Short-Course Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GOTHENBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Olympic Champion Claudia Poll
of Costa Rica took off with a flying start at the World
Short-course Swimming Championships here as she won the 200 meters
freestyle heat on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 1.91-meter freestyler from the tiny South American nation,
double gold medallist at the 1995 World Short-course Championships
in Rio de Janeiro, led the way throughout and touched the pad with
a winning time of one minute 57.90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Poll, who claimed the first Olympic gold for her country in the
200m freestyle at the Centennial Olympic Games in Atlanta last
summer, showed the absolute advantage in her speciality, beating
her closest opponent Martina Moravcova of Slovakia, 1995 bronze
medalist, by nearly half a second.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cuba's Rodolfo Falcon failed to enter the final in
his defense of the men's 200 meters backstroke title, managing
only the 19th-fastest overall time of 2:00.46.
</P>
<P>
China's Wang Wei clocked fastest time of 1:55.13 to become the
event's top qualifier.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese swimmer Lu Donghua led the way in 59.94,
winning the women's 100m back heat, ahead of Germany's Olympic
silver medalist Sandra Voelker and American defending champion
Misty Hyman.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Voelker lowered her own European 50 meters freestyle
short-course record with 24.62, becoming the top finisher in the
qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
World record-holder of the event Le Jingyi of China,
third-finisher in Thursday's 100m freestyle, was third in the heat
overall, behind Jenny Thompson of the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
