<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National Economy Grows steadily (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's national economy reported
a smooth growth in the first quarter this year, showing a sound
development trend following its "soft landing" 1996, a senior
official with the State Statistical Bureau (SSB) said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Ye Zhen, spokesman for SSB,
said that the bureau's preliminary estimates show that China's GDP
reached 1,468.6 billion yuan, representing a year-on-year increase
of 9.4 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Such an increase margin is 0.8 percentage points lower than in
the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the figures of the corresponding period of 1996,
the increases of the country's primary, secondary, and tertiary
industries were five percent, 10.6 percent and 8.3 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the agricultural sector was off to a good start in
the first quarter, as the SSB survey on the planting intentions of
40,000 farmer families showed that the crop planting acreage will
reach 153 million ha this year, up 10.5 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The acreage planted with cereal crops will be 400,000 ha more
than that of last year, hitting 110 million ha in total.
</P>
<P>
He said that a good harvest of summer grain crops is expected,
as long as no severe natural disaster occurs in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the January-March period, the industrial sector reported a
steady growth, with all the enterprises above county level
generating an added value of 452.5 billion yuan, a year-on-year
growth of 11 percent. This increased margin is 2.6 percentage
points down from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The sale-to-production ratio edged up, registering an average
of 93.96 percent in the country during the first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
