<HEADLINE> Turkish Clubs To Compete in European Champions' League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Turkish clubs will be eligible
to compete in the expanded European Champions' League next season,
UEFA announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision means that Greece will have only one team in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
According to the UEFA regulations, the top eight countries in
rankings in Europe can each field two teams in the competitons,
one seeded and one entering the qualifying rounds.
</P>
<P>
Countries ranked ninth to 16th can field one team in the
Champions' League.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece were level in eighth place on the rankings,
which is based on points gained in European club competitions over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
UEFA used a tie-break method of taking this season's
co-efficient points into consideration and on that basis Turkey
had 7.75 points and Greece 3.75.
</P>
<P>
The competition is used as a qualifying tournament for the UEFA
Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National Economy Grows Steadily (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Ye, investment in fixed assets stood at 147.8
billion yuan, up 13.9 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Consumer goods maintained a balance between supply and
demand. Retail sales of consumer goods shot up 15.5 percent over
1996, at 663.3 billion yuan. When adjusted for inflation rate, the
real increase is 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that, in contrast to slack foreign trade of
the January-March period of 1996, exports scored rapid growth in
the first quarter, thanks to the brisk international market.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, in the first quarter, imports and
exports totaled 64.3 billion US dollars, up 11.6 percent over the
same period of last year. Exports amounted to 33.5 billion
dollars, up 25.7 percent, but imports inched down 1.8 percent to
28.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices inched up 2.6 percent, comparing with the same
period of last year; and consumer prices went up by 5.2 percent on
average in the first quarter. The inflation rate showed a monthly
decline, and reached the lowest point in March, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income of urban residents was 1,446 yuan,
representing a real increase of only 1.2 percent over the same
period of last year. Farmers' income was 564 yuan per person, an
increase of 1.5 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that, although the national economy maintained its
healthy growth, bottlenecks like the irrational industrial
structure and increasing losses of the state-owned sector were
far from solved.
</P>
<P>
The government should improve its regulation of the economy and
its role in "fine tuning" the economy to continue the healthy
economic development marked by high growth and low inflation, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
