<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Nepalese Lawmaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
met here today with a delegation from the Foreign Affairs and
Human Rights Committee of the Nepalese parliament, led by the
Committee Chairman Jaya Prakash Prasad Anand.
</P>
<P>
Describing China and Nepal as good neighbors, Li said that
friendly exchanges between the people of the two countries date
back to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the leaders of the two countries have had
frequent exchanges of visits in recent years, which has promoted
friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Nepalese friendship has stood the test of time, he said,
setting a fine example for friendly co-existence between countries
with different social systems.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to develop its cooperative relations with
Nepal on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Li also highly appreciated the "one China" stance observed by
all the previous Nepalese governments, and expressed thanks to
Nepal for its support to China on the issues of Tibet, Taiwan, and
human rights.
</P>
<P>
"We agree to engage in friendly dialogues on an equal footing
in human rights issue, but never agree that human rights issue can
be used to interfere in other countries' internal affairs," he
noted, "For developing nations, top priority should be given to
the rights of survival and development."
</P>
<P>
Li also briefed the Nepalese visitors on China's achievements
since it began its reform and opening-up policy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Anand said that bilateral relations have always grown smoothly,
and cooperation between the two countries in various areas has
progressed.
</P>
<P>
Anand reiterated that the Nepalese government never allows
anyone to participate in activities aimed at splitting China in
Nepalese territories, and will continue to follow its "one China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is ready to cooperate with China in the human rights
area, Anand said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
