<HEADLINE> Tung Appeals for HK Government's Cooperation on Right of Abode Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa today
urged the Hong Kong government to cooperate with his team in
laying out the post-handover law on the right of abode issue.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at his office, Tung confessed that
drafting the bill, which is among those things his office must do
before July 1, is not an easy job.
</P>
<P>
So he hoped that the Hong Kong government, which has
"repeatedly pledged support and cooperation after he was elected
Chief Executive," would lend a hand in this respect in the
interests of the 6 million Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
With the Hong Kong government's help, his office could do
better and more smoothly and avoid possible mistakes in drafting
the law.
</P>
<P>
However, the chief executive pointed out, if the Hong Kong
government refuses to change its mind, his team will work on their
own and try their best to draft the legislation.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill will be then submitted to the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC), the legislative arm of the HKSAR, for
passage before July 1.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference which lasted some forty minutes, Tung
also answered questions on the consultation document his office
released last week on the amendments to the Societies Ordinance
and the Public Order Ordinance.  
</P>
