<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister on China-ASEAN Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The third political consultation
between senior officials from China and the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan Thursday told
reporters that the two sides discussed specific proposals for the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Tang described the consultations as friendly and harmonious,
adding that common understanding and cooperation were the focus of
the consultations.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN is pleased with China's economic achievements, and
hopes that the China will continue to play an important role in
ensuring regional stability and development, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
China supports the ASEAN's efforts to raise regional
cooperation, and is ready to enhance coordination with the ASEAN,
Tang continued.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that China's counterparts were briefed on China's
principled stance on the country's peaceful reunification, its
opposition to Taiwan's independence, and the Hong Kong issue, and
expressed thanks to the ASEAN countries for their understanding
and support to China in the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN reaffirmed that it will adhere to the "one China"
policy, Tang said, regarding China's resumption of its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1 as an end to its colonial
history and demonstrating Asian revitalization.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that the ASEAN countries extended congratulations to
China for its foiling for the seventh time an anti-China draft
resolution on the human rights issue proposed by some Western
countries.
</P>
<P>
On existing differences concerning borders and territories
between China and some ASEAN nations, Tang said that the Chinese
side reiterated its position, and that the two sides expressed the
will to maintain regional peace and stability, and that it is
imperative to handle differences through negotiations in order to
seek a proper settlement, not allow the differences to interfere
in the normal development of relations between countries.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also exchanged views on international and regional
situations, as well as upcoming dialogues between Chinese and
ASEAN foreign ministers in July.
</P>
<P>
The consultations proceeded smoothly in a wide range of areas,
Tang noted, providing easy access for the two sides in promoting
ties.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances of a global multipolar trend, he said,
the two sides have achieved a remarkable progress in their
relationship in recent years, and bilateral ties have entered a
new era marked by a long-standing stability and more maturity, on
the basis of their common understanding that as developing
countries, China and the ASEAN nations face the same task of
advancing their respective economies, and show their strong
willingness to safeguard peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
As the ASEAN countries are China's neighbors, he noted, China
places importance on its friendly cooperation with the
association, and cites it as an important part of the country's
good-neighbor foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides hold that they should promote bilateral cooperation
in all fields, to establish a neighborly partnership toward the
21st century based on equality, mutual benefit, and trust, beyond
their specific and temporary differences," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tang also said that China attaches importance to the role
played by the ASEAN in regional affairs, and that in the post-Cold
War, the ASEAN has become an active, influential organization in
the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"We speak highly of the achievements made by the organization,
and support the ASEAN's development," he said, "This not only
conforms to a global multipolar trend, but benefits long-term
peace and development in the Asia-Pacific region." 
</P>
</TEXT>
