<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chemical Warfare Victims Urged to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian authorities today called
on the chemical warfare victims to end their on-going strike and
leave the case with the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Rowhani, Vice-Speaker of the Parliament and secretary of
the Supreme National Security Council, assured the war veterans
disabled by chemical poisons that the Parliament would deal with
their grievance.
</P>
<P>
The vice-speaker said that the legislature would adopt
necessary measures against the 24 German companies which supplied
chemical weapons to Iraq during the eight-year war with Iran in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 chemical warfare victims and their families
have staged a sit-in in front of the German Embassy since
Wednesday and they vowed to continue the protest until
their demands for actions against the German officials and firms
were met.
</P>
<P>
They condemned the ruling of the Berlin court that the Iranian
leadership was behind the 1992 killings of four Kurdish
dissidents, and demanded an official German apology to the Iranian
nation.
</P>
<P>
Iran claimed that a total of 118 war veterans wounded in Iraqi
chemical attacks have died since 1991 and thousands of war
victims are suffering from severe injuries sustained from the
Iraqi chemical warfare during 1980-1988.
</P>
<P>
Hamid Sohrab-Pur, head of the Center for Victims of Chemical
Warfare, said that his center has so far obtained medical records
of 60,000 out of an estimated 100,000 chemically wounded.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, 1,500 of such people living in various
parts of the country need constant medication.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that those behind such crimes have been
identified and that the center holds a list of German companies
responsible for the chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
He said that his center has already cooperated with German
medical centers for treatment to the disabled Iranians.
</P>
<P>
The German physicians treating the victims are expected to shed
light on the realities, but none of them was available for comment
so far.
</P>
<P>
By persuading the disabled to end their protest, Iran seemed to
intend to show its willingness to come down from a political
crisis with Germany, its largest European trade partner, after
several days of anti-German demonstrations throughout the country
this week.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Tehran would not like to go too far in
relations with Germany in particular and the European Union as a
whole after ambassadors were recalled from each other's capitals.
</P>
<P>
As the U.S.is still striving to isolate Iran, the Islamic republic
would play into the hands of Washington if it goes to sever ties
with the European countries. Berlin, while defending the court
verdict from Tehran accusations, has also tried to distance
itself from the U.S. drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
