<HEADLINE> China Expects More Cooperation on Securities Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's new securities market
needs more cooperation from Asia-Pacific securities organizations,
Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji told a meeting this afternoon with
people here to attend an Asia-Pacific conference of the
International Organization of Securities Commission (IOSCO).
</P>
<P>
After being briefed on the meeting and relevant securities
regulations of other countries and regions, Zhu gave an brief
account of China's securities market, saying that under the Deng
Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, China's securities market has been developing
gradually along with the deepening of the country's reform and
opening up.
</P>
<P>
The securities market is playing an active role in raising
construction funds and facilitating the transformation of
enterprise management mechanism, he noted. However, he added, the
market is still imperfect and needs to be further developed by the
means of perfecting the legal system, strengthening regulation and
education on awareness of risk.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that securities regulatory organizations
of Asia-Pacific states and regions will increase exchanges and
cooperation and make a joint effort to help develop the securities
market in this region.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of securities regulatory organizations from 16
Asia-Pacific states and regions, including the China Securities
Regulatory Commission, attended the three-day meeting, which ended
today. 
</P>
