<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Kills 60 Sudanese Soldiers, 60 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army has killed 60
Sudanese soldiers and 60 Ugandan rebels, capturing another 164 in
a near-border clash in northern Uganda, local newspaper "the New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, Uganda State Minister for Defense, confirmed on
Thursday that some two companies of Sudanese army and two
companies of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) rebels were
involved in the battle in Lelabur, close to the Uganda-Sudan
border on April 14.
</P>
<P>
"Sixty Sudanese armed forces were killed and 114 captured.
Sixty-eight LRA bandits were killed and 50 either were captured
or surrendered," Mbabazi said in a official statement.
</P>
<P>
The combined forces of the Sudanese soldiers and Ugandan
rebels had an intention to establish a base in northern Uganda to
collect intelligence for an offensive by Sudanese army and LRA,
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The captured Sudanese soldiers and Uganda rebels now are held
in the barracks of the fourth division in northern Uganda and the
full names of the captured Sudanese soldiers will be published
later, it said.
</P>
<P>
Two Ugandan soldiers gathering intelligence about LRA rebels
were missing in action in Sudan, the state minister said. But he
refused to give details, adding that Uganda's only interest in
Sudan is to collect intelligence about LRA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
