<HEADLINE> Britain to Train Sierra Leonean Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- British military experts will
train two battalions of the Sierra Leonean army in all military
operations from April 20, according to a bilateral military
agreement signed here earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The British training team, which is already in the west
African state, is headed by Major Lincoln Jack under the
supervision of the British Military Attache in the British High
Commission in Accra, Colonel Keith Faith.
</P>
<P>
The agreement did not state how long the program will last,
but observers said senior and junior officers and other ranks of
the Sierra Leonean army will take part in discipline and conduct
training as well as the role of the army in a democratic society.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Tejan Kabbah and British High
Commissioner in Freetown Peter Penfold inked the agreement on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah said in a statement after the signing that the British
training program is a demonstration of Britain's desire for
"sustainable development and peace" in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Penfold, who signed on behalf of the British government, said
the agreement "demonstrates a commitment by Britain to peace and
stability in the west African state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
