<HEADLINE> Warm Weather Prompts Early Appearance of UK's Butterflies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The warm weather has speeded up
the development of butterflies to such an extent that many species
are on the wing more than a month earlier, a report by the British
Butterfly Conservation said here today.
</P>
<P>
Nigel Bourn, an authority, said, "It's incredibly early for
butterflies. They are cold-blooded and are dependent on
temperatures to develop."
</P>
<P>
When it is this warm and this early they will develop very
quickly. It's always difficult to be absolutely sure if it's a
record but they are on the wing earlier than at any time in living
memory, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ecologists and regional recorders from the charity have noted
that it is not only one individual butterfly being sighted. They
are being reported in considerable numbers.
</P>
<P>
Dr Warren said butterflies were good indicators of global
climate changes. A recent northward spread of species, such as the
gatekeeper and speckled wood and the current early appearances,
was a good witness, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
