<HEADLINE> Mobutu-Kabila Peace Talks Likely in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited peace
talks between Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader
Laurent Kabila is likely to take place in South Africa early next
week.
</P>
<P>
At a media briefing in Cape Town, presidential spokesman Parks
Mankahlana made it clear that Mobutu had received an invitation
from South African President Nelson Mandela, a major mediator of
the Zairean civil war, through his special envoy Honore Nganda.
</P>
<P>
Following his talks with Kabila Wednesday night and
discussions with Ngbanda later on, Mandela on Thursday extended a
formal invitation to Mobutu to meet Kabila in South Africa "as
soon as possible".
</P>
<P>
Ngbanda left Cape Town for Kinshasa, capital of Zaire, on
Thursday to deliver Mandela's invitation to Mobutu, and a
response was expected later today, said a South African
government source.
</P>
<P>
Although it has not yet been decided where the proposed talks
will take place, Cape Town is a likely venue.
</P>
<P>
In Zairean capital of Kinshasa, President Mobutu's son and
spokesman, Nzanga Mobutu, confirmed on Thursday that his
66-year-old father now was willing to meet the rebel leader,
but adding that the president refused to step down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, United Nations special envoy on the Zairean crisis,
Mohammed Sahnoun, said on Thursday that the ultimate goal of a
direct meeting between Mobutu and Kabila would be to organize the
terms for elections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Cape Town, where Mandela's meeting with Kabila
took place, Sahnoun said both sides had agreed to meet with no
preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The rebel forces led by Kabila, have now controlled over a
half of Zaire's territory, and are still pushing forward with
capital Kinshasa as their final target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
