<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Employees Earn More in 4th Quarter of 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Employees in financing,
insurance, real estate and business services made money faster
than those engaged in other industry sectors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Average payroll per person in the financing services recorded a
year-on-year increase of 10.5 percent in nominal terms or 4.2
percent in real terms in the fourth quarter of 1996, according to
the latest government statistics. The big rise was partly boosted
by the issue of more bonuses to employees.
</P>
<P>
The Census and Statistics Department said today that the
average labor earnings in all major sectors, as measured by
payroll per person, went up by 10.1 percent in nominal terms in
the final quarter of 1996. The real increase stood at 3.9 percent
after discounting changes in consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale, retail, trade, restaurants and hotels registered the
slowest growth in average payroll per person -- 6.1 percent in
nominal terms and 0.1 percent in real terms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
