<HEADLINE> Fresh Riot Breaks Out in Nigeria's Oil City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Fresh riot broke out in southern
Nigeria's oil city Warri on Thursday, with youths from two ethnic
groups exchanging gun fire on the street.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said today that one of the combatants were
confirmed killed in the shootout, while a major market and a
police station were torched in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Women market peddlers were caught between the warring youths
and the policemen who came to arrest the situation.
</P>
<P>
Tear gases were fired by the police, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts in Warri started about a months ago, following
the relocation of the South-West local government headquarters
from the Ijaw community to the Itsekiri community.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between the Ijaw and the Itsekiri people have
led to the death of at least 44 people so far and caused a huge
loss to the oil companies operating in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Delta State Government had called in the federal navy
force and imposed a curfew to restore peace in the city, but had
failed to solve the disputes between the tribes.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's trouble started when the Itsekiris found on the
roadside of the body of an Itsekiri chief's son. They then
stormed the Dawudu Police Station, saying that the police had
failed to protect them during earlier Ijaw attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
