<HEADLINE> Bomb Blasts at UK Rail Station, Highways Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A small bomb exploded at a railway
station in Leeds in northern England this morning, Britain's
railroad and police said.
</P>
<P>
The blast took place at 8:17 local time in a car park adjacent
to the railway station, forcing police to close off areas of Leeds
city center, but there were no injuries, local television reported.
</P>
<P>
Police also carried out a controlled explosion at Stoke railway
station in northwest England, and were still busy searching for
more possible explosive devices in the warned areas, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion followed telephoned bomb warnings at 7:10 this
morning which said bombs had been planted at key railway stations
and on the M6 motorway, bringing traffic chaos to northwest
England.
</P>
<P>
A total of four railway stations, including Doncaster, Crewe
and Stoke-on-Trent, and two motorway junctions were sealed off and
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
This cut off the main north/south rail lines on both the east
and west sides of Britain as well as one of the two main highways
linking the north and south of the country.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major accused the IRA of the
incidents at his daily press conference. He said, "This looks very
much at the moment as though this is the work of the IRA showing
their usual contempt for people's lives and for property."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
