<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Kidnappers Killed in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government forces
killed six kidnappers at about midnight Thursday in Zamboanga city
in the southern Philippines, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces' Southern Command said the six killed were
members of a kidnapping group, which ambushed the mayor of Siocon
town near Zamboanga city at noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of the 32nd Infantry Battalion based in Siocon had
pursued the kidnapping group and chanced upon it at Siay village,
Siocon early Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
They killed the group's leader during the encounter, then
ambushed and killed five other kidnappers, who came back to
retrieve the body of their slain leader.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapping group was reportedly composed of renegade
members of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping syndicates have been rampant in the Philippines,
especially in southern Mindanao island, for years.
</P>
<P>
Facing a public outcry against the surging kidnapping cases,
the government has vowed to crack down on kidnapping syndicates
operating in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
