<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese Province Smoothing Graves into Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
leveled 1.6 million graves into more than 3,300 ha of farmland
during the ongoing spring sowing season.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers have razed or relocated the graves of their
deceased, in response to the provincial government's call to make
more room for farming. Shandong is under pressure from the
decreasing area of farmland and the increasing population.
</P>
<P>
Taking the lead in the campaign, the Party secretary and the
head of Chengyang Township in Qingdao city smoothed graves, and
the work for the whole township was completed within three days.
</P>
<P>
Officials working in Beijing, Shanghai, and other places went
back to their hometowns in the province on hearing the
announcement, and leveled graves there.
</P>
<P>
Different measures have been taken to properly dispose of the
ashes taken from the graves. Qingdao held ceremonies on March 27
and 28 for casting ashes into the sea. Some ashes were buried and
trees were planted on the sites to honor the dead. Other ashes
were placed either in memorial halls or in public cemeteries.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Not to Join NATO, Finnish PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Finland will maintain its
"nonalignment" security policy without seeking to join an enlarged
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Kyodo News Service
quoted Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, now on a four-day visit to Japan, told Kyodo Thursday
that Finland could best serve its interests and stability in the
region by remaining nonaligned.
</P>
<P>
"We want to maintain independent and credible defense," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to NATO's eastward expansion, Lipponen said, "What is
our concern is NATO enlargement should not result in a new
division" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the European single currency, Lipponen reiterated
Finland's policy of seeking to participate in the first wave of
European Monetary Union scheduled for January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish Prime Minister showed confidence that the European
single currency will be launched in January 1999 as scheduled,
brushing aside lingering doubts about the plan.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, who arrived in Tokyo Wednesday, has met with several
Japanese government, parliament and business leaders, including
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-more details added Chinese, Egyptian Leaders Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng and visiting
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal Ahmed El-Ganzouri, in a meeting this
morning at the Great Hall of the People, spoke about developing
the stable friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Egypt was the first African Arab state to
establish diplomatic relations with China, and that the efforts of
the older generation of leaders of the two countries provided a
firm foundation for a sustained development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past nearly 50 years, China and Egypt have forged a
sincere friendship and cooperation based on mutual respect and
understanding, in spite of turbulent changes in the world, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the 90's, Sino-Egyptian ties entered a new era
of development and that the two countries have had exchanges and
cooperation in politics, agriculture, science and technology, and
culture.
</P>
<P>
Li noted out that China and Egypt have similar views on many
major international issues and have cooperated in human rights,
arms control, and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government has supported China's reunification
cause, Li said, praising its principled stand on the "one China"
policy and pledging not to have official exchanges with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
El-Ganzouri said that China is a great country and that the two
countries have a long-term friendship, and that Egypt admires
China for its reforms and opening up policy and its achievements.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Egypt is glad to see the return of Hong
Kong under the principle of "one country, two
systems". Reaffirming Egypt's "one China" position, El-Ganzouri
said that his country supports the entry of China into the World
Trade Organization and opposes interference in other countries'
internal affairs, using human rights as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China and Egypt have similar conditions and that
both face the task of developing the economy, and that China has
always viewed Egypt as its important partner among Arab states. He
said that the two have no conflict of interest and that it is
China's principle to strengthen friendship and cooperation with
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
China views Sino-Egyptian ties from a strategic viewpoint, Li
said, and is willing to forge long-term and stable friendship and
cooperation with Egypt under the principle of mutual respect,
equality, and reciprocity for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China is also willing to use this relationship as an example of
cooperation among developing countries, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
