<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Keep Tighter Rein on Green Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's stock market is in
another bullish run, but frequent warnings of stock investment
risks from government officials and stock analysts have sounded an
alarm for investors eager to take advantage of the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Hammering an awareness of investment risks into the investors'
mind is the top priority at present, and we have to set up a
complete risk-control and management system and fight vigorously
against market irregularities of all kinds," warned Zhou
Zhengqing, chairman of the Securities Committee of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the ongoing International Organization of
Securities Committee (IOSCO) Asia-Pacific Regional Committee
Conference and Enforcement Meeting, Zhou pointed out that
regulation and standardization of the market will remain a
long-term guiding policy of the government, in view of the fact
that the Chinese securities market is still immature.
</P>
<P>
After runaway price hikes which started last October and a
quick recovery from the sharp plunge last December, the stock
market in China rode on another strong yet steadier upward trend
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Composite Stock Index climbed to a record 1,338
points last Wednesday, with the Shenzhen Composite Stock Index
hovering well above 4,700 points.
</P>
<P>
A stock-buying craze has swept throughout China, with investors
lured by the attraction of a big but seemingly too-easy
fortune. There are now over 24 million stock trading accounts
registered in China and the figure is still rising.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts from the China Securities Co. Ltd. said stock
prices are already too high to be safe in the eyes of the
government.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthened supervision" and "risk prevention" have become
the guidewords of officials and analysts. And the industry
watchdog, China Securities Regulatory Commission, has shown great
enthusiasm for learning from international experience so as to
practice more effective regulation and standardization of the
securities market.
</P>
<P>
The commission has signed an agreement with six overseas
regulatory bodies and plans to sign a seventh on Friday with the
Securities Commission of Malaysia, to get a firmer grip on
supervising and regulating the securities market.
</P>
<P>
A standardized market calls for a perfected regulatory
framework. The government has issued a series of provisional
regulations in recent years, and the draft Securities Law is being
examined by the nation's legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Severe penalties face market violators, including those
securities outlets which provide overdrafts for institutional
investors and who trade stocks on margin.
</P>
<P>
To ease the strained market, the government also announced a
quota of four billion yuan in convertible bonds and planned to
select a group of state enterprises in backbone industries to
issue such bonds.
</P>
<P>
"This act is aimed at increasing market supply and financial
investment instruments to lessen the pressure on the stock market,
and it indicates the government is turning to market-based
leverages in market regulation rather than the past administrative
means," said an analyst with the China Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
