<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (29-30) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (29-30)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Are Hong Kong residents who hold British Dependent
Territories Citizens (BDTC) passports Chinese Citizens?
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to Article 33 of the Chinese Constitution,
all people with the nationality of the People's Republic of China
are Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Article 2 of the Nationality Law of the People's Republic of
China says that the People's Republic of China is a unified,
multi-ethnic state and people of all ethnicities are all of
Chinese nationality.
</P>
<P>
Article 3 of the Nationality Law says that China does not
recognize double nationality of a Chinese citizen.
</P>
<P>
In its memorandum to the British government in 1984, the
Chinese government clearly states, "All Hong Kong Chinese
compatriots, whether or not they hold the 'British Dependent
Territories Citizens' Passports, are Chinese citizens."
</P>
<P>
This is a proper solution of the nationality issue for Hong
Kong residents in the light of realities in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Question: After 1997, what differences will there be in the
political rights of Chinese nationals and non-Chinese nationals
among Hong Kong residents?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Among the Basic Law's provisions on the rights and
duties of Hong Kong residents, an important issue concerns
nationality. There are indeed differences between Chinese
nationals and non-Chinese nationals among Hong Kong residents with
regard to political rights.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the Constitution and the Nationality Law, the
Basic Law sets great store by the principles of national unity and
sovereignty, stipulating that, in the Hong Kong SAR, the Chief
Executive, principal officials, members of the executive council,
president of the Legislative Council and chief judges of the Court
of Final Appeal and the High Court must be Chinese citizens among
permanent residents of Hong Kong who have no right of abode in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the Basic Law, the region's Legislative
Council are to be composed mainly of Chinese citizens who are
permanent residents of the region with no right of abode in any
foreign country; and permanent residents of the region who are not
of Chinese nationality or who have the right of abode in foreign
countries may be elected members of the Legislative Council of the
region, but the proportion of such members may not exceed 20
percent of the total membership of the Council.
</P>
<P>
To sum up, only Chinese citizens among permanent Hong Kong
residents who have no right of abode in foreign countries are
eligible for election to the above-mentioned posts and 80 percent
of the seats of the Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Article 21 of the Basic Law stipulates, "Chinese citizens who
are residents of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region shall
be entitled to participate in the management of state affairs
according to law. In accordance with the assigned number of seats
and the selection method specified by the National People's
congress, Chinese citizens among residents of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall locally elect deputies of the
Region to the National People's Congress to participate in the
work of the highest organ of state power."
</P>
<P>
It is evident that only Hong Kong residents of Chinese
nationality have the political right to elect, or stand for
election as, deputies to the National People's Congress and
participate in the administration of state affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
