<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Leader to Give State of Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The guerrilla-turned governor of
the Philippine Muslim autonomous region, Nur Misuari, will give
his first State of Region Address on April 28 since taking office
last October.
</P>
<P>
This was announced today by Kabelan Sema, speaker of the
Regional Legislative Assembly of the Autonomous Region of Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM), according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sema said Misuari will deliver the State of Region Address at
the opening ceremony of the next session of the Regional
Legislative Assembly (RLA).
</P>
<P>
Expected to be reported by Misuari is his performance for the
past seven months of being the region's chief executive, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the RLA's meeting will be Philippine Senate
President Ernesto Maceda, Speaker of the House of Representatives
Jose de Venecia, and several diplomatic corps from member
countries of the Organization of Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
Sema praised Misuari for his efforts in bringing economic
development and political stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said many foreign investors, mostly Malaysians and
Indonesians, have committed to pour investments into the
poverty-stricken region.
</P>
<P>
But Misuari's critics have slammed him for failing to crack
down on criminals, particularly kidnap-for-ransom groups, who were
doing their business in almost all ARMM provinces.
</P>
<P>
Last November, a surge of kidnappings had prompted local
business groups, mostly of Filipino-Chinese descent, to launch the
first-ever anti-crime protest action in Catabato city in central
Mindanao, where Misuari's governor office is based.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, chairman of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF),
was elected as governor of the ARMM last October during a direct
election held in all ARMM provinces.
</P>
<P>
Misuari signed a peace deal with the government last September,
ending nearly three decades of conflicts between the MNLF and the
government troops in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Misuari also chairs the Southern Philippines Council for Peace
and Development, which was created under the peace accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
