<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City to Attract Investment From Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The city of Wuzhou in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has paved the way for
attracting investment from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wuzhou, located 436 km from Hong Kong, has nearly 50,000
natives who have settled in Hong Kong and are expected to help
promote economic contacts between the two places.
</P>
<P>
Wuzhou has so far received 120 million US dollars of investment
from Hong Kong and set up over 400 enterprises, accounting for
more than 80 percent of the number of local overseas-funded
companies.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the exports in Wuzhou, or over one billion yuan,
is brought in by the local Hong Kong-funded enterprises, which
conduct business in the fields of industry, agriculture,
processing, real estate, transportation, and services.
</P>
<P>
The city has drawn up a series of flexible policies covering
transfer and use of land, fee charges, rent of factory buildings
and foreign trade, in a bid to encourage Hong Kong business people
to invest locally.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wuzhou has injected nearly 300 million yuan to
improve the local investment environment. As a result, the city
has built an airport and two container harbors with handling
capacity reaching 300,000 tons and 500,000 tons, respectively,
added 53,000 lines of program-controlled telephones, extended a
highway linking with Shenzhen, and set up bonded warehouses for
the processing trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
