<HEADLINE> India's Congress Formally Extends Support to UF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress Party today
formally extended its support to the 13-party United Front (UF) in
forming a government under a new leader by writing a letter to the
president in this regard, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party, which pulled down the UF government led by
Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda by withdrawing support at the end
of last month, renewed its support to the Front in a resolution
adopted on April 15 but did not submit a letter to President
Shankar Dayal Sharma to establish the support.
</P>
<P>
A copy of the letter written by the Congress Party's President
Sitaram Kesri was also delivered to the UF leaders who met here
this morning to discuss the crucial leadership issue.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party has set a change of leadership in UF as a
precondition to extend support to the Front in forming an
alternate government.
</P>
<P>
UF spokesman Jaipal Reddy welcomed the Congress Party's move,
saying that the Front is reviewing the content of the letter.
</P>
<P>
The letter submitted by the Congress Party to the president is
expected to speed up the process for the UF to elect a new leader
in place of outgoing Prime Minister Deve Gowda.  
</P>
