<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Invests Heavily in Water Conservation Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has invested a record of more than four billion yuan in
water conservation facilities by mid-March this year, accounting
for over one tenth of the national total in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The province was hit by a huge flood in 1994, causing great
damage and casualties.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Guangdong has stepped up efforts to turn around the
traditional concept of water conservation merely for agriculture,
and to establish a new idea that water conservation is a basic
industry in national economic development and people's life.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong put more than 17 billion yuan in water conservation
construction during the Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995),
and will invest another 50 billion yuan by 2005 to change the
situation in which flood prevention capacity lags behind economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Feilaixia Water Control Project and other dykes and
dams projects will form an anti-flood shelter in the Pearl River
Delta area to fight the most serious flood possible in 300
years. Cities with population above 500,000 are required to build
water control facilities that can fight the serious flood possible
in 100 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
