<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Red Cross
committee today expressed the hope to contact with its counterpart
in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to discuss the
provision of food aid and relief goods to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was raised by South Korean Red Cross President
Kang Young-hoon to his DPRK counterpart Li Songho in a direct
telephone message this morning.
</P>
<P>
Kang Young-hoon suggested that both committees send a
three-member delegation headed by each other's secretary-general
to the truce village of Panmunjom to discuss the delivery of the
aid from South Korea to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Kang expressed his concern about the "difficult
food situation in the North (DPRK)".
</P>
<P>
So far, the assistance to the DPRK provided by South Korea was
mainly transferred by the International Red Cross League and other
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government decided on March 31 to allow
non-governmental organizations to provide food assistance to the
DPRK. But the aid must be delivered exclusively through the
channel of Red Cross. 
</P>
