<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memorial Hall Reopens to Mark Great Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province recently reopened a memorial hall, closed for nearly ten
years for renovation, to commemorate the great Chinese writer Lu
Xun.
</P>
<P>
The hall, built in 1957, is under state protection.
</P>
<P>
Seventy years ago, the local government rebuilt rooms and
hallways to reveal their original condition, and a photography
retrospective was set up to help people know more about the life
of Lu, also known as a great revolutionary and thinker.
</P>
<P>
On display are more than 430 black-and-white photos, 139
documents, 13 editions of the "Complete Works of Lu Xun" and 435
items of the writer's personal belongings from throughout his life.
</P>
<P>
The hall was built on the site of the former Zhongshan
University, which was founded by Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the forerunner
of China's democratic revolution. Lu was a professor at the
university and lived there for a while.
</P>
<P>
There are three other memorial halls for the writer, one in
Beijing, one in Shanghai and another in Shaoxing, east China's
Zhejiang Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
