<HEADLINE> Indian President in Bid to End Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Shanker Dayal
Sharma has begun a serious exercise to seek an early end to the
current political crisis by talking to top political leaders in
the country, the Hindustan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The president on Thursday held separate meetings with Congress
party President Sitaram Kesri, general secretary of the Communist
Party of Indian (Marxist) H. S. Surjeet and Bharatiya Janata Party
leader Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
Caretaker Prime Minister H. D. Deve Gowda also had a meeting
with the president on Wednesday night to discuss the political
situation.
</P>
<P>
Sharma's discussions with the political leaders were seen as
"anxiety" on his part to resolve the deadlock and intended to get
first-hand knowledge of the efforts undertaken by them in the last
few days for forming the next government to avoid premature
dissolution of the Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament),
officials close to the president said.
</P>
<P>
The United Front government led by Prime Minister Deve Gowda
lost a vote of confidence on April 11 following the withdrawal of
support by the Congress party.
</P>
<P>
However, the efforts made by the Congress party and the United
Front to form an alternate government to avoid a snap poll have
been stalled over a procedural issue.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted on April 15, the Congress party said
that it will extend support to the United Front to form a new
government after the front chooses a new leader in place of Deve
Gowda.
</P>
<P>
However, the United Front, especially the left parties in it,
insisted that the Congress party first withdraw a claim it staked
on April 1 to form a government before the front changes its
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Though the Congress party makes it clear that it will recall
the claim from the president after a change of leadership in the
front, the latter refuses to buy the idea saying there is a "game
plan" behind.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
