<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Backs Romania's Bid for EU, NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy fully supports Romania's bid
for membership of the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said today.
</P>
<P>
Romania's integration into NATO among the first wave of new
members "is what we propose and what we want," Dini said, after
meeting his Romanian counterpart, Adrian Severin, here.
</P>
<P>
In supporting Romania's bid, Italy expects to help the EU and
NATO to "keep getting stronger," he said.
</P>
<P>
A NATO summit scheduled for July is expected to announce the
first group of nations to be admitted to NATO.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland are widely expected to
be the first countries invited to join, followed by Romania.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that during his meeting with Severin, he thanked
Romania for its participation in the Italian led multinational
force to safeguard humanitarian aid to Albania. Romania will send
400 soldiers to take part in the United Nations approved
6,000-strong mission.
</P>
<P>
Romania's participation was important as the operation was "a
European NATO exercise", Dini added.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi also met Severin today to
discuss bilateral ties and Romania's early admission to the EU and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
The planned NATO expansion was strongly opposed by Russia,
which believes the military alliance's eastward enlargement would
threaten its national security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
