<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Parties in Nepal Demand Right to Choose Symbols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Small political parties in
Nepal have called on the government to ensure their right to
choose symbols for the local elections next month.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of 17 parties Thursday handed over memorandums to
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and the Election Commission
in protest against the Commission's earlier decision to distribute
election symbols to the small parties arbitrarily.
</P>
<P>
The small parties are those who won less than 3 percent votes
in last elections.
</P>
<P>
The parties, led by the Nepal Workers and Peasants' Party
(NWPP) which has three MPs in the 205-seat lower house, said that
the commission's decision, which ruled out the use of their own
symbols, was a conspiracy by big parties to curb the growth of
smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the Election Commission, the decision
on small parties' symbols was made in accordance with the
country's law concerning local elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Chand reportedly has pledged to try to
sort out the problem by holding necessary discussions with the
Chief Election Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is to hold the elections for chief officers and
representatives of over 4,000 local administration bodies across
the country from May 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
