<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academic Accuses U.S. Authors of Fabricating Quotes  (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese academic has
accused two U.S. authors of fabricating quotes in their recently
publised book on Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Mi Zhenyu's article, entitled "Foolish Lies -- A Comment on
'The Coming Conflict With China,'" was published by the Chinese
press today. The full text of the article reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
I have recently read the book "The Coming Conflict With
America" written by Richard Bernstein and Ross H. Munro, former
Beijing-based foreign correspondents for Time magazine and the
Toronto Globe and Mail respectively.
</P>
<P>
What shocked me is that the authors' headline quotation in the
book's introduction quoted remarks attributed to me that I have
never made. The quote said, "(As for the United States) for a
relatively long time it will be absolutely necessary that we
quietly nurse our sense of vengeance... We must conceal our
abilities and bide our time." (The ellipsis existed in the
original quote.) The authors of the book did not provide the
exact source of their quote but just said "in a widely published
1996 collection of essays by several Chinese officials." Among
the books published in China in 1996, only one book, "Megatrends
China," published by Hua Ling Publishing House, carried one of my
articles called "China's Strategic Policy on Positive Defense."
</P>
<P>
In my article, I elaborated the theory that China's military
strategic policy can only be one of "active defense," determined
by the nature of the country, its social system, basic domestic
and foreign policies, and the tasks of its armed forces, as
stipulated in the Chinese Constitution.
</P>
<P>
China's military strategy is subordinate to and serves the
basic policy of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the
constitution, which defines that the nature of the nation's
military strategic policy is one of self-defense and defense.
</P>
<P>
I also pointed out in the article that China advocates avoiding
and stopping war, and settling international disputes and issues
left over from history by peaceful means instead of resorting to
war, and that preventing war constitutes an important part of the
strategic policy of active defense in the new era.
</P>
<P>
I didn't mention the United States anywhere in the article, nor
did I say anything similar to that quoted in the U.S. book.
</P>
<P>
If the two authors of the book think I said what they quoted on
some other occasions or in some other articles, then they should
show me the evidence. If not, the quote they attributed to me is
nothing but sheer fabrication.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to understand why the two authors turned a deaf ear
to the principles of "increasing mutual trust, reducing trouble,
developing cooperation and avoiding confrontation," which
President Jiang Zemin has stated repeatedly to guide Sino-U.S.
relations.
</P>
<P>
They are obsessed with using other people's names to invent
lies and to escalate the hostile atmosphere between China and the
United States, so as to deceive and mislead the world opinion.
</P>
<P>
To support the "China Threat" theory, the two authors turned
right and wrong upside down, confused black with white and made up
facts to support their views to vilify and demonize China's
politics, economy, diplomacy and human rights conditions. China's
defense and military policy was especially a primary target for
their vicious attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academic Accuses U.S. Authors of Fabricating Quotes  (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The authors made a big issue of China's defense spending,
saying China's "actual" annual defense budget should be 10 times
the amount of what was announced and therefore has reached a level
of "87 billion U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
As is well known, China's per capita defense spending is among
the lowest in the world. In 1996, it was seven dollars, while
that of the United States was 996 dollars and Japan 360 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending per serviceman in the United States in 1996
was 178,300 dollars and in Japan 188,000 dollars, while it was
less than 3,000 dollars in China, 1.7 percent of the U.S. level
and 1.6 percent of Japan's.
</P>
<P>
The absolute level of China's defense spending was lower than
that of South Korea and China's Taiwan province, not to mention
the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Japan and other
western countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the United States spent 263.9 billion dollars on
defense, Britain 32.5 billion, France 38.3 billion, Germany 31.9
billion, Japan 45.1 billion, South Korea 15.6 billion and China's
Taiwan province 13.6 billion, while China spent only 71.5 billion
RMB yuan, about 8.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's total revenue in 1996 was 736.6
billion yuan (88.7 billion dollars) and total expenditure was
791.4 billion yuan (95.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
If China spent 87 billion dollars on defense, as the authors
claimed in their book, it would mean that 90 percent of China's
fiscal expenditure in one year went to national defense.
</P>
<P>
I would like to ask the authors that if this was true, where
had China got the money to invest in infrastructure construction,
the development of education, science, healthcare, cultural
service and to improve the people's living standards? And how
could China have achieved the rapid economic growth?
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that the authors' views are too ridiculous to be
taken seriously. No wonder some American scholars have strongly
criticized the authors since the book was published, saying that
the view of "China Threat" they alluded to was "an exaggerated
view just to scare people." Furthermore, they have accused the
two authors of analyzing issues on China with improper reference
materials and being "too perfunctory" in making judgements on
China's international policies.
</P>
<P>
I would like to point out that there have always been a handful
of people in the United States who are unwilling to see China
becoming a unified and powerful country as well as Sino-U.S. ties
being improved.
</P>
<P>
Whenever China scores points in developing its economy or
whenever Sino-U.S. relations are improved, those people feel
uneasy, and act to fabricate the theory of "China Threat," racking
their brains to play up a media campaign to reduce confidence,
make more troubles, obstruct cooperation and trumpet confrontation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
China's late leader Deng Xiaoping pointed out that China and
the United States should be able to turn their relations for the
better eventually.
</P>
<P>
I would like to advise those people like Bernstein and Munro
not to lift a rock which will only drop on their own feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
