<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Troops to Enter Albanian Port Vlore Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The first contingent of Italian
troops is expected to enter Albania's southern port of Vlore no
later than early next week, Italian Defense Chief of Staff Admiral
Guido Venturoni said here today.
</P>
<P>
Venturoni said the Italian force will move once the
multinational protection force is fully established in the capital
city Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Following the Albania's largest port of Durres in the west and
Tirana airport, Vlore is the third key port of entry into Albania
that the 6,000-strong force from eight countries wants to secure.
</P>
<P>
The port is a hotbed for insurgence after anger over failed
investment schemes, in which many Albanians lost their life
savings, turned violent in January.
</P>
<P>
The relative delay in establishing a bridgehead in Vlore,
compared to those in Durres and Tirana, was due to technical not
political considerations, he added.
</P>
<P>
So far, Venturoni said, about 1,800 men have been deployed in
various parts of Albania as part of the so-called Operation
Alba. They are 717 Italians, 450 French, 359 Spanish, 125 Greeks
and 169 Turkish.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the first four Italian coast guards units, assigned
to patrol the Albanian coastline and ports under the agreement
between Rome and Tirana, left Italian southern port of Brindisi
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Before taking up service, the ships will first take on Albanian
liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
Ferry transport between Italy and Durres, interrupted on March
13, will also resume Friday. First passengers will be Operation
Alba men, while civilian service is expected to resume on April
28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
