<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chubais Urges to Review 1997 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- First Russian Vice Premier Anatoly
Chubais today called for a review of the 1997 federal budget
because its targets cannot be met in the current crisis, Itar-Tass
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Federation Council (upper house), Chubais, who
is also the finance minister, noted that Russia is living through
"an outrageous budget crisis," -- but not through a disastrous
slump.
</P>
<P>
He said the budget exceeded the ability of the state to pay by
100,000 billion roubles (about 17.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Chubais said revenue targets in the first quarter were met by
only 56.6 percent and expenditure by 62.8 percent, while the tax
collection was only met by 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that a review of the budget was "absolutely
necessary," adding that proposals would be submitted to the
Russian parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
Chubais stressed that the main task was to adopt a program for
emergency revenues, totaling 30,000 billion roubles.
</P>
<P>
Referring to 1998 budget, Chubais said the Russian
Administration would call the first meeting on it in May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about payment of wages and pension arrears, Chubais
confirmed that pension arrears would be paid by July 1, 1997, and
transfer debts to regions would be fully paid by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the government intended to connect the
amount of benefit payments to the level of wellbeing in families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
