<HEADLINE> ASEAN Offers Promising Opportunities to Developed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- With an average economic growth
rate of 6-7 percent a year, ASEAN countries, particularly
Indonesia, offer promising business opportunities to developed
countries, an Indonesian businessman said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a businessmen's dialogue held in Yogyakarta,
Central Java, Thursday, executive chairman of the First ASEAN
Business Summit 1997 (FABS '97) Suryo B. Sulisto said the ASEAN
countries' success in attaining high economic growth had been
widely recognized by developed countries, reports reaching here
today said.
</P>
<P>
To maintain growth at the same pace, the ASEAN countries needed
to ensure the continuity of conducive social, political and
security conditions, he noted.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations), which comprises
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam, was now also the fourth biggest entity in world trade
after the United States, Japan and Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
The value of trade transactions between ASEAN and non-ASEAN
countries had reached around 700 billion US dollars, while
intra-ASEAN trade was recorded at only 100 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to spur investments should continuously be encouraged
particularly in Indonesia, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the FABS '97 held on March 9-10 in Jakarta, many investment
opportunities with bright prospects had been identified, which
included infrastructure covering the construction and installation
of telephone, electricity, ports, toll roads and irrigation
networks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
