<HEADLINE> Probe on Nepali Former Government's Fall Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A panel of Nepal's opposition
has concluded that no party leader should bear the responsibility
for the fall of the former government last month, sources here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The three-member investigation committee of the Nepali Congress
(NC) party, formed earlier to probe the cause behind the defeat of
a confidence vote for the NC-led coalition government in early
March, Thursday completed its report, ruling out any conspiracy
within the party.
</P>
<P>
The report will be made public after it is further evaluated
and approved by the NC party's Central Working Committee, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The former coalition government of Sher Bahadur Deuba, a young
generation NC leader, collapsed after losing the confidence vote
directly due to two NC MPs' deliberate absence from the voting
session in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Lokendra Bahadur Chand, a leader of NC's former ruling partner
the National Democratic Party (RPP), formed the present government
last month under an alliance with the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), the largest party in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers earlier reported that Chand had managed to
lure away the two NC lawmakers from the parliamentary voting in
order to bring down the NC-led coalition government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
