<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Prospects for Maldivian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Maldivian economy was poised
to improve with the two main industries, tourism and fisheries,
providing a strong base for growth, according to a report reaching
here from Male today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the outlook for the Maldives remains positive
with GDP growth expected to average 6 percent a year in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
A continuing tight monetary policy plus an increase in the
number of tourists and a higher fish catch led to a marked
economic improvement in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Real gross domestic product growth in 1996 was estimated at 6.5
percent while inflation was at 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Reduced public spending and a tight monetary policy are
expected to keep inflation subdued at about 3 percent in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
The exceptionally high rates of economic growth reached in
1985-90, more than 10 percent per year, could not be repeated in
the near future due to capacity constraints in both tourism and
fisheries, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Authorities Seek Termination to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadoran authorities proposed
today to the leaders of a health workers strike to search for a
solution considering the difficulties the country is going
through.
</P>
<P>
Up to 28,000 doctors and 14,000 other medical workers have been
on strike for three days in demand of a budget increase, from 2.8
to 12 percent, for the public health sector.
</P>
<P>
Health assistance centers remain closed and medical care is
given only to the extremely urgent cases.
</P>
<P>
"The country is going through difficult circumstances, and
hence solutions must be found jointly by various sectors and the
national government," said acting President Fabian Alarcon.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador saw a political crisis since the Congress impeached
President Abdala Bucaram Ortiz and forced him to step on February 6.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever might be the case, the government wants to give all
the priority and agility to the solution of this problem," Alarcon
said.
</P>
<P>
Taking the stoppage as one of the points he concerns most,
Alarcon is planning to intervene in the conversations and to
establish a plan of action and a calendar of work.
</P>
<P>
But Health Minister Guillermo Wagner said it is impossible to
meet the demand of 12 billion sucres (approximately 3.1 million
U.S. dollars) for bonuses, although other solutions are being
explored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
