<HEADLINE> Northwest China Waving Visitors Nearer To Grape Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Turpan city along the Silk Road
in northwest China will hold its annual grape festival on August
26-30, as a part of the nationwide campaign: Visit China '97.
</P>
<P>
The festival will be followed by the Urumqi Economic
Cooperation and Foreign Trade Fair on September 1-8, today's China
Daily quoted Li Donghui, vice-chairman of the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, as saying at the ongoing 81st Guangzhou
Commodities Fair.
</P>
<P>
Turpan has long been famous for its grapes, particularly the
seedless white, mare's nipple, red grape and purple grape, and for
its historical sites, such as the ancient city ruins of Gaochang
and Jiaohe, the Astana Ancient Tombs, Karez Wells, Bezklik
Thousand Buddha Caves, and Emin Minaret.
</P>
<P>
The grape city also takes pride in its Grape Valley, Flaming
Mountains, Aydingkol Lake, the second lowest place in the world,
and Sand Therapy Center, where rheumatoid arthritis is said to be
cured naturally. Visitors can also appreciate the ethnic Uygurs'
folk culture.
</P>
<P>
"The festival will also offer business opportunities for
enterpreneurs at home and abroad," said Abla Kasim, deputy
magistrate of the Turpan Administrative Office.
</P>
<P>
The past five Urumqi fairs collected business deals worth of
5.6 billion US dollars, and reported more than 2.3 billion US
dollars of overseas investment from 65 countries and regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
