<HEADLINE> North China's Port City Strengthens Vehicle Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin is increasing its efforts to control pollution from
vehicle exhaust fumes.
</P>
<P>
With the number of the city's vehicles exceeding 600,000,
pollutant discharge has also been increasing. Statistics from the
environmental monitoring department reveal that the automobile
exhaust fumes has become the city's biggest mobile air pollution
source.
</P>
<P>
The city has set up a task force to control the vehicle
pollution in order to protect people's health.
</P>
<P>
The task force requires the automobile and motor-makers meet
the government standards in production, and strictly controls the
sale of vehicles that fail to meet the discharge standards.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's mobile monitoring groups have been making regular
checks of the vehicles on the road. Those exceeding the discharge
standards will be forced to improve before they can run on the
road again.
</P>
<P>
The city's efforts at air pollution control has made it one of
the country's best environmental cities for two consecutive
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
