<HEADLINE> Six Sri Lankan Soldiers Killed in Mine Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Six Sri Lankan soldiers including
an officer were killed in a mine blast at Nagarkovil in the Jaffna
peninsula Thursday, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether the mine had been laid by Tamil rebels
sometime earlier or it had been set up specially to blow up the
vehicle in which the government soldiers were traveling, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that the attack had come when troops had
observed major movements of rebel cadres northwards from the east.
</P>
<P>
However, there had not been any mine blast in the Jaffna
peninsula during the past few weeks although yesterday's blast was
the most serious this year.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil
rebels, who have been waging a 14-year war for a separate state
in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Having lost their heartland the Jaffna peninsula since last
May, they have been pushed into jungle hideouts from where they
have been launching sporadic attacks on army camps and mobile
patrols.  
</P>
</TEXT>
