<HEADLINE> Former Rebels to Integrate With Philippine Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Final integration of the 1,500
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) members into the Armed
Forces was scheduled for September this year after they finish six
months of training, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
These MNLF members, who gained qualifications to join the
Philippine military earlier this year, has started training
courses this month, Victor Garcia, armed forces chief for
civil-military affairs, was quoted as telling a press briefing
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said training centers for the successful applicants are
located all over Mindanao island, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF, formerly the largest Muslim rebel group in the
southern Philippines, concluded a peace deal last September with
the government, ending nearly three decades of war in the south
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal, the military should integrate 5,500 MNLF
members into their ranks while another 2,000 members are to be
absorbed by the Philippine National Police.
</P>
<P>
Garcia also denied earlier reports that some 5,000 MNLF members
have defected to the breakaway Moro Islamic Liberation Front
because of dissatisfaction over the "slow-paced" integration of
the MNLF into the military.
</P>
<P>
He said the report was another "propaganda ploy" of the MILF in
view of the success of the integration program of the military.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, currently the largest anti-government force in the
country, refused to accept the MNLF-government peace deal and
sought its own peace talks with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
