<HEADLINE> China's Small Firms Compete Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China strives to help its small
and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) to enter the world market,
"China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qingtai, vice-minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, made the pledge Thursday at the end of a two-day work
conference.
</P>
<P>
As China has become a member of Apec and its entry into the WTO
is on the agenda, China's SMEs will be exposed to fierce
international competition both at home and abroad, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered to support the SMEs, as they are not
capable on their own of coping with the complexities of the world
market, he added.
</P>
<P>
China will set up a service system, which will assist SMEs in
the fields of financing, market access, information, technology
and human resources, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The practice is in line with the requirements of Apec's
Platform for SMEs and aims to transform China's SMEs into
creative, market-oriented, competitive entities.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental organizations will also play a vital role in
establishing the system, as they have more advantages in promoting
service-system related information exchanges and attracting
investments from other Apec member countries.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to be made by the government include the
completion of an information consulting center and a personnel
training center in the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Trade with Apec member countries is also an important part of
the SMEs' aim of breaking in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Sino-German bilateral co-operation on SMEs is developing
rapidly, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China will help its SMEs to extend co-operation
with partners in Japan, Korea, Italy and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
