<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Deplores U.S. Trade Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Argentina deeply deplored
U.S. withdrawal of preferences to Argentine products because it
alleged that the Argentine laws refused to protect U.S. trademarks
and patents from local manufacturers of pharmaceutical products.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.S. Commerce Representative Marlene Barchevsky
published here today, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido di Tella
said that the U.S. move did not "agree with the excellent
relations of our countries."
</P>
<P>
Barchevsky announced the withdrawal of U.S. Generalized System
of Preferences to Argentine products on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Argentina would suffer a loss of 8-12 million U.S. dollars for
higher tariffs because of the U.S. move. Last year, Argentina
earned 118 million dollars from its pharmaceutical products on the
U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed that the move has a bigger political
clout than economic one, because the U.S. places Argentina among
those countries which do not respect intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
"Argentina is convinced that its legislation on patents of
pharmaceutical products and industrial secret fulfillment, and in
some aspects, goes beyond" what is established by the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Di Tella said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. pharmaceutical trans-national companies, whose
pressures resulted in the sanctions, said they suffer losses of up
to 500 million dollars a year because of the "piracy" of Argentine
pharmaceutical companies which dominate the market here.
</P>
<P>
The White House objects to the Argentine laws that give local
companies the deadline of the year 2000 to comply with the
obligation of paying royalties on the use of foreign patents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIVB Awards Hosts to Youth, Junior Volleyball Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea was picked up by the
FIVB to host the 1999 men's youth world volleyball championship,
the sport's governing body said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dominica will chair the women's youth edition in 1999 when
Saudi Arabia hosts the men's junior volleyball championship with
Portugal playing host to the women's junior event.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were announced by FIVB president Ruben Acosta at
the 50th anniversary of the International Volleyball Federation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the 26th FIVB congress will be held on October 28-30,
1998 in Tokyo, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
