<HEADLINE> OSCE Envoy: Election Crucial to Albania Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The international mediator Franz
Vranitzky said here today that a free and fair election "is of
great significance to the stability in Albania."
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky, an envoy of the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), hoped that different political
forces in the country could cooperate to create a sound condition
for the parliamentary elections due by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
He said the OSCE and European Commission fully supported the
election and would send experts and observers there.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky, who is on a two-day visit to Albania, said after his
talks with Albanian President Sali Berisha that the political
parties had agreed to hold the election by the end of June, but
still differed on election procedure, and issues concerning the
media during the vote.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky unexpectedly cancelled a trip to the rebel-held
southern town of Vlore Thursday after talks with Berisha.
</P>
<P>
His spokeswoman, Melissa Fleming, said: "He wants to focus on
the situation here and on preparing for elections."
</P>
<P>
This is Vranitzky's third visit to Albania as an international
mediator.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been swept by two months of chaos after an
insurrection sparked by the collapse of get-rich-quick pyramid
"investment" schemes. Nearly 300 people have died.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky expressed the OSCE's support for the election
Wednesday, one day after the Italian-led multinational force
started its operations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council passed a resolution on
March 25 authorizing the dispatch of a 6,000-member, Italian-led
multinational force for three months to protect relief operations
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 Italian, French and Spanish soldiers landed in
Albania Tuesday and began to take control of harbors, airports and
other main communication facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
