<HEADLINE> Community Services Booming in South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- More and more community centers
are popping up in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
Province, providing local residents with at least 60 inexpensive
services ranging from babysitting and medical treatment to
electrical appliance repair and cleaning clogged drainpipes.
</P>
<P>
The city is encouraging people to spend their spare time
helping neighbors who don't have the time or the skills to take
care of household and family-related chores. One community center
reported that more than 1,000 people have been involved in
assisting nearly 40,000 residents in the area.
</P>
<P>
Community helpers include teachers, workers, doctors and
self-employed people, who fill out applications detailing what
types of services they can provide.
</P>
<P>
"If people in trouble call us, we will arrange for our staff to
help them," said Hu Xiaoling, head of a service center, adding
that the charge is quite small.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the city bureau of civil affairs show that 87
percent of neighborhood committees have set up centers to lend a
hand to the disabled and the elderly, and more than 60,000 young
people have participated.
</P>
<P>
After six months' training guided by volunteer physicians,
Huang Xiaoli, a 27-year-old woman whose right leg is deformed, was
able to ride a bike. She gained fresh confidence and got a job in
a dressmaking factory.
</P>
<P>
The city government recently decided to allocate 500,000 yuan
per year to boost community services, and a local welfare fund
contributed one million yuan to aid construction of
facilities. Enitem
nnnn
</P>
