<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholar Calls for Translation of More Foreign Literature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A noted Chinese scholar says that
the country should continue to introduce foreign literature into
China.
</P>
<P>
"The work will help Chinese readers enjoy and study foreign
culture, and help Chinese writers learn some modern ideas about
literary creation," said Shen Huihui, deputy-editor-in-chief of
the magazine "World Literature."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, she said that literary works from
some 120 countries have been translated into Chinese over the past
20 years, but that's still not enough.
</P>
<P>
"World Literature," the country's leading publication for
foreign literature, was founded by Lu Xun, China's literary
pioneer, in 1934. It was banned during the Cultural Revolution
(1966-76) when foreign literature was regarded as having a
corruptive influence on Chinese readers.
</P>
<P>
But the magazine resumed publication in the late 1970s when
China opened to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the magazine has introduced thousands of writers
throughout the world into China, said Shen, a Harvard University
graduate who now works at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
(CASS).
</P>
<P>
Readers in developing countries have attached great importance
on Modernism, Post-modernism and folk literature, she noted.
</P>
<P>
For example, "Ulysess" by James Joyce has been translated by
one of Shen's colleagues.
</P>
<P>
And the recent focal point is the "literary explosion" in Latin
America, which Shen believed can inspire Chinese writers'
imagination and aspiration.
</P>
<P>
But she said that the work is hindered because the commercial
sector is more interested in popular works by writers like US
author Michael Crichton, who penned the thriller "Jurassic Park."
</P>
<P>
And like many of the Chinese magazines engaged in foreign
literature, a shortage of funding is the chief obstacle preventing
them from buying copyrights from foreign authors.
</P>
<P>
Chinese publishing houses print more than 1,000 titles of
translated books every year. The country publishes some 100,000
new books annually.
</P>
<P>
China bans the translation of books deemed to have violent or
pornographic content.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vigilant Against Medfly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese inspection officials are
urging nationwide efforts to halt the entry of a bee-like insect
called the Mediterranean Fruit Fly (Medfly) into the country.
</P>
<P>
They said that the insect may cause mammoth economic losses for
fruit growers, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The Administration of Animal and Plant Quarantine of China
(CAAPQ) has repeatedly confiscated Medfly-infested fruit carried
into China in passenger luggage through the country's ports in
recent years, an official at the administration noted.
</P>
<P>
Yang Weichang, director-general of CAAPQ's Tianjin branch said
that his inspection team found live Medflies inside five oranges
carried in by a Belarussian passenger from Minsk at Tianjin's
international airport.
</P>
<P>
China previously found Medflies at least six times at its
customs locations in southern areas over the past few years, while
the insect was seldom seen in the north until recently.
</P>
<P>
The Medfly eats more than 250 kinds of fruits and vegetables
and reproduces quickly. The world's scientists have not yet found
an effective way to kill the Medfly, which has already spread to
more than 80 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"Once this kind of insect comes into China, it will not only
cause damage to the country's fruit production but will also
affect China's foreign trade," said Zhao San, an expert with
CAAPQ's Tianjin branch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Price Index in China's Major Cities in January, February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The consumer price index for
residents stood at an average of 105.9 points in 35 major Chinese
cities in the January-February period, taking the composite price
index of the same period of 1996 as 100, said the latest
statistics from the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The biggest increase margins was registered in three inland
cities -- Xi'an, Chengdu and Xining.
</P>
<P>
In Xi'an, the consumer price index for residents was 112
points, while that for Chengdu and Xining stood at 110.1 and
108.7, respectively. 
</P>
