<HEADLINE> Records Performances Feature Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Two world records were
shattered by the Australian men and Chinese women as the World
Swimming Short Course Championships took off in Gotenborg on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian quartet bettered the 4x100-meter medley relay
record of 3:30.91 in 3:30.66.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 4x200 freestyle relay, Chinese Chen Yan, Nian
Yin, Shan Ying and Wang Luna finished with 7:51.92, surpassing
their own world record of 7:52.45.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lars Frolander of Sweden set two game records in the
the 100-meter butterfly. And his winning mark of 51.95 in the
finals bettered the newly record of 52.10 set by himself in the
preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Dunn of Australia swam home in 4:06.89 in the 400-meter
medley, beating his own championship record of 4:08.02 set in Rio
de Janeiro in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In her first short-course meet ever, American Jennifer Thompson
won the 100-meter freestyle, beating Germany's Sandra Voelker and
world record-holder Le Jingyi of China to second and third.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's Gustavo Borges took the 200-meter freestyle in 1:45.45
and Liu Limin of China won the women's 200-meter butterfly in
2:07.20.
</P>
<P>
Hitomi Kashima of Japan finished second while America's Misty
Hyman who recorded the fastest in the heats, swam home a bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
Emma Johnson of Australia took the women's 400-meter medley in
4:35.18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
