<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Arrest 21 Protesters in Diet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo police today arrested 21
people who shouted protests from the House of Councillors gallery
during Diet (parliament) deliberation on a bill to allow the
continued compulsory leasing of land in Okinawa for use by the
United States military.
</P>
<P>
The group ignored orders from House of Councillors President
Juro Saito to keep quiet. The protesters kept shouting for about
13 minutes and forced the upper house to interrupt deliberation
for five minutes, police said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were taken into custody by parliamentary guards
later and delivered to police, who arrested them on the charge of
obstruction of business.
</P>
<P>
Diet business resumed following the melee, and the government
proposed bill became law after the upper house passed it.
</P>
<P>
The enacted revision of the 1952 law ensures that the
U.S. forces can continue to use lands owned by 3,000 people
scattered among 12 U.S. military facilities on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
Okinawans were disappointed in the passage of the bill.
Demonstrations by lawyers and local residents were held in Tokyo
and Okinawa after the bill was enacted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
