<P>
The men's singles champion will win 415,000 pounds (673,000
U.S. dollars), while the women's top prize is 373,500 pounds
(606,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The WTA Tour's argument is that equal prize money should be
paid from the quarter-finals onwards.
</P>
<P>
"It's still the public's view that they prefer the men's
matches to the women's," Wimbledon chairman John Curry said,
hinting it was impossible to close the gap.
</P>
<P>
Total prize money has risen by 6.5 percent to 6.88 million
pounds (11.2 million U.S. dollars) and for the first time
incorporates "per diem" payments to players in the qualifying
tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
