<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information, Imaging Technology Takes Big Strides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The information and imaging
technology has made great strides over the past few years with the
joint efforts of computer companies and imaging equipment makers.
</P>
<P>
The annual exhibition of the Association for Information and
Image Management International, which closed here at the Center of
New York today, further broadened people's view scope of how
modern technology is changing the way of information flow and
management.
</P>
<P>
Marry Lurie, one of the organizing officials of the show, said
that the changing nature of the use and value of information makes
its timely delivery and analysis a business imperative.
</P>
<P>
More than 340 companies seem to have brought such a message to
the show that turning tons of static sheets of paper or microfilms
into images which can be edited and sent about through computer
systems is no longer a tough issue.
</P>
<P>
The New Jersey-based Panasonic U.S. Company displayed its
latest high-speed color scanner, which can scan 40 pages a minute
and has a one million page duty cycle. Its resolution ranges
between 150 and 300 dots per inch, with a 256-level grayscale.
</P>
<P>
Microfilm scanning and printing system has become even more
compact in size and powerful in function. The MS-500 produced by
Canon U.S.A. Inc. can easily read and transfer microfilm images
into personal computers. It can be connected directly to a laseer
printer to print out images the user has selected. With the help
of OCR software, images can even be edited and transferred to
other computers.
</P>
<P>
Another dramatic characteristic is the rapid progress in the
data storage on compact discs (CD) with more efficient CD
recording machines being produced.
</P>
<P>
Higher resolution digital cameras coupled with color printers
or copy machines have turned mass production of high quality
digital images an easy job.
</P>
<P>
Software companies are turning out power weapons for document
capture, storage, retrieval, display, workflow and management, all
of which are highly automated.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said at least 35,000 visitors had appeared at the
show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
