<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Economic, Trade Seminar on China Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 17 (xinhua)-- An economic and trade seminar on
China ended here today with more than 200 Chinese and American
business people having attended it.
</P>
<P>
Promoting trade between Houston and China was the focus of the
10th Annual International Business Seminar held in the Southern
U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, named "Target The Chinese Market," was organized
by the Great Houston Partnership composed by the Chamber of
Commerce of Houston and other economic development and trade
groups.
</P>
<P>
At the opening meeting, Sun Zhenyu, head of a Chinese economic
and trade delegation and Vice Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation of China, said that the seminar will deepen
the understanding between the business people of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
To further develop the healthy economic and trade relations
between China and the U.S. is not only in the basic interests of
the people of the two countries, but also to contribute to the
political stability and economic prosperity of Asia and the world,
the head of the Chinese delegation said.
</P>
<P>
Sun also stressed at a luncheon speech that the Chinese and the
U.S. economics are highly complementary and the U.S. is able to
play extensive roles in the process of China's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The topics discussed at the seminar included seeking of
information on the Chinese market and distribution stategies,
invitation of foreign business to the Chinese market and efforts
to find trade and joint venture chances.
</P>
<P>
Li Decheng, executive vice mayor of Shenzhen, which has a
sister city relations with Houston, introduced the economic
situation in the city and invited Houston trade groups to increase
their investment and trade in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The one-day seminar was held a day before the Houston
International Festival honoring China which opens Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
