<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says NATO-Russia Deal Not Completed, Date for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that the date for signing a document between the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) and Russia has yet to be fixed since
the negotiations have not been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Russian President Boris Yeltsin said after
meeting German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the German city of
Baden-Baden that an agreement governing relations between Russia
and the alliance will be signed in May.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Michael McCurry told reporters that "we
are, obviously, continuing to work very hard with other members of
the alliance to finalize a charter document" with Russia.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that such an agreement would be "truly historic."
"There will need to be an appropriate occasion to finalize that
charter," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The venue has not been determined, nor the date, because among
other things, the charter itself hasn't been finished," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a separate regular news briefing, State Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns said, "The negotiations have not been
completed, and so we can't cite a victory before we have it."
</P>
<P>
"We haven't decided quite where a conference would be between
Russia and NATO, but if we do work out an agreement, we'll
certainly schedule one and late May would be very good timing
indeed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that a NATO-Russia agreement could be signed on
May 27 in Paris. Kohl also indicated that 90 percent of the
document has been completed and a full agreement will be finalized
before May 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Senate Agrees to Vote on Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate unanimously
agreed today to vote on the ratification of the Chemical Weapons
Convention (CWC) on April 24.
</P>
<P>
The convention, signed by 161 countries and ratified by 70,
will take effect with or without the United States on April 29. If
the Senate fails to approve it, the U.S. will fail to participate
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has launched a campaign to persuade
senators to pass the treaty before it takes effect while opponents
led by Republican Senator Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, vowed to block it until last minute.
</P>
<P>
Three former U.S. defense secretaries today issued a joint
statement, urging the Senate to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Former defense secretaries William Perry, Harold Brown and
Eliott Richardson joined the current defense secretary, William
Cohen, in backing the treaty, which bans the development,
production, stockpiling, transfer and use of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that U.S. ratification of the CWC will
contribute significantly to the security interests of the United
States and safety of our armed forces," the three former defense
secretaries in the brief statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement released by the Pentagon said, "In light of the
decision under President Reagan to get rid of the vast majority of
U.S. chemical weapons stockpiles, it is in our interests to
require other nations to do the same."
</P>
<P>
Also today, Chairman John Shalikashvili of the Pentagon Joint
Chiefs of Staff reiterated his appeal to the Senate for ratifying
the convention.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, four other former defense secretaries --
Dick Cheney, Caspar Weinberger, Donald Rumsfeld and James
Schlesinger -- urged the Senate not to ratify the treaty, arguing
that the treaty is not in the interests of the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970418.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says No More Food Aid for DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not
provide any more food aid to the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) in spite of its new demand for international
assistance to meet the severe food shortage, U.S. officials said
today.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters that
the United States had already provided 25 million dollars in rice
and grain for the DPRK's food shortage since February this year,
and would not consider to pledge more.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has done what it can in committing to 25
million dollars in food aid. I am not aware of any initiative with
the State Department or the U.S. government to try to see if we
would ratchet that up," he said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Burns again denied there were any links between the food aid
and a U.S.-South Korean proposal for four-party peace talks,
saying, "We don't believe it is wise to link questions of food
delivery with political questions."
</P>
<P>
DPRK officials held a meeting Wednesday in New York with U.S.
and South Korean officials over the U.S.-South Korean proposal.
Both sides agreed that the meeting would adjourn Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles
Kartman, the most senior American representative at the talks in
New York, the DPRK officials appeared ready to accept the
proposal, but they were also demanding more food aid.
</P>
<P>
"The North Koreans have raised over and over again that their
highest priority is food, and we have raised again and again our
desire that they participate in the peace talks," Kartman told
members of a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
