<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Hosts Child Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Hillary Rodham Clinton today hosted an early child development
conference.
</P>
<P>
Child care soon emerged as a key issue at the White House
Conference on Early Childhood Development and Learning, which was
beamed to 92 locations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
T. Berry Brazelton, a pediatrician and author who charged the
president and lawmakers, "turned the wrong way" on welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
"We should have looked at what we were going to do with
children before we pushed women out into the workplace. It's so
obvious to anybody," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Harvard Medical School professor was one of several experts
criticizing government shortcomings that ranged from a lack of
universal health care for children, inadequate prenatal and
post-partus counseling for women to a general lack of support for
parents.
</P>
<P>
David Hamburg, president of the Carnegie Corp. of New York,
said, "The fact is our nation's infants and toddlers are in
trouble."
</P>
<P>
Clinton agreed a more "systematic" approach was needed to
ensure basic services and said federal research was needed to
determine such things as how much interactive time a parent should
spend with an infant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
