<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto to Visit Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto will make a working visit to Washington next
week, the White House announced today.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was reported to bring "welcome news" to President
Bill Clinton: Japan has enacted a law giving the government
authority to force property owners to lease land for U.S. military
bases on Okinawa in accordance with a security treaty between the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The law was approved less than a month before thousands of
leases expire on Okinawa, which hosts two-thirds of 47,000 U.S.
troops stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Residents on Okinawa are increasingly opposed to U.S. military
presence as it brings noise and crime. In 1995, three U.S.
soldiers raped a 12-year-old Okinawan girl, which touched off
nationwide protests against American savagery, and Okinawans
demanded that U.S. troops go home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
